  ('gsoc-owasp-securecodebox-defectdojo-go', 'OWASP secureCodeBox — DefectDojo Hook Rewrite in Go', 'Replace the JavaScript DefectDojo persistence hook in secureCodeBox with a Go service that pushes finding payloads through the DefectDojo REST API while running natively as a Kubernetes operator. Goal is faster reconciliation and smaller container images.', 'Read github.com/secureCodeBox/secureCodeBox and pick the persistence-defectdojo hook directory. Compare the existing JS code path with the DefectDojo REST API docs at defectdojo.github.io/django-DefectDojo/integrations/api-v2-docs/.

Mentor Jannik Hollenbach reviews PRs on GitHub; the project chat is owasp.slack.com #project-securecodebox. Kustomize and Helm chart templates already exist, so your Go binary just needs to fit the same image conventions.

Deliverable: a Go controller that watches Scan CRDs in a kind cluster, parses the SARIF output and creates corresponding findings in a local DefectDojo with TLS and retries.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'OWASP', 'GSoC', 'GSoC 2023', 'https://owasp.org/www-community/initiatives/gsoc/gsoc2023ideas', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com/secureCodeBox/secureCodeBox","url":"https://github.com/secureCodeBox/secureCodeBox","kind":"repo"},{"label":"github.com/DefectDojo/django-DefectDojo","url":"https://github.com/DefectDojo/django-DefectDojo","kind":"repo"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['go','kubernetes','security','devsecops','operator']::text[]),
  ('gsoc-roscontrol-tutorials', 'Open Robotics — Industrial Robot Hardware Examples for ros2_control', 'Author end-to-end ros2_control tutorials that cover a 6-DoF industrial arm, a mobile base and a parallel-jaw gripper — including SystemInterface, controller configuration and Gazebo simulation. Output ships into the official control.ros.org docs.', 'Read control.ros.org and clone github.com/ros-controls/ros2_control plus ros2_control_demos. Pick a free industrial arm URDF — e.g. the ABB IRB1200 — and stand up an example hardware interface.

Mentor Bence Magyar runs the weekly ros2_control working-group meeting; meeting notes live on the ros-controls/roadmap repo. Join the ROS Discourse and ros.org wiki to introduce yourself.

Final deliverable: a ros2 launch file that brings up the arm in Gazebo Ignition, loads the JointTrajectoryController and follows a moveit-planned trajectory, with the full README walking new users through every command.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'Open Robotics', 'GSoC', 'GSoC 2022', 'https://control.ros.org/galactic/doc/project_ideas.html', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com/ros-controls/ros2_control_demos","url":"https://github.com/ros-controls/ros2_control_demos","kind":"repo"},{"label":"control.ros.org/","url":"https://control.ros.org/","kind":"docs"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['c++','python','ros2','robotics','control']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-neurips-machine-unlearning-2023', 'NeurIPS 2023 — Machine Unlearning', 'Erase the influence of a requested subset of training samples from a deployed model without retraining from scratch and without harming overall accuracy. Submissions were judged on a privacy attack score combined with retained utility on held-out data.', 'Begin with the starter notebook that loads the provided CASIA-style face recognition checkpoint and the forget-set indices. The reference approach is fine-tuning with a contrastive loss on the retain set while applying gradient ascent on the forget set — but pure ascent diverges quickly, so clip gradients and interleave retain steps.

The scoring system runs a membership inference attack on your unlearned model and compares it against a fully retrained reference. A common pitfall is over-unlearning, which collapses accuracy on the retain set; track both retain-accuracy and the MIA AUC simultaneously. Bad-Teacher and SCRUB are strong baselines worth implementing.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google Research, NeurIPS', 'Kaggle', '2023', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/neurips-2023-machine-unlearning', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/neurips-2023-machine-unlearning/data","format":"PyTorch checkpoint + image set"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','research','privacy','neurips','unlearning']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-nips-2017-adversarial-attack', 'NIPS 2017 — Non-targeted Adversarial Attack', 'Imperceptibly perturb ImageNet images so that an unknown ensemble of classifiers misclassifies them. Submissions ran as Docker containers and were scored by the average misclassification rate across hidden defender models.', 'Start with the FGSM and Basic Iterative Method baselines from Cleverhans — they fool a single white-box model trivially but fail to transfer. The winning team introduced Momentum Iterative FGSM (later published at CVPR 2018), which adds a velocity term to gradient updates to escape poor local maxima.

Dockerise your attack early — late submission failures often came from missing CUDA libraries. Ensemble surrogate models (Inception v3, ResNet, ensemble-adv Inception v3) when computing the gradient, otherwise transferability collapses against hardened defenders.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google Brain, NIPS', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/nips-2017-non-targeted-adversarial-attack', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/nips-2017-non-targeted-adversarial-attack/data","format":"ImageNet PNG subset"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','adversarial','research','neurips']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-birdclef-2023', 'BirdCLEF 2023 — Bird Call Identification', 'Identify Eastern African bird species from short soundscape recordings captured by passive acoustic monitoring devices. Submissions had to score 264 species across non-overlapping 5-second segments under a kernel runtime constraint.', 'Convert raw OGG audio to log-mel spectrograms (128 mels, 32 kHz sample rate, 5-second windows) and treat the problem as multi-label image classification. EfficientNet-B0 with mixup and pink-noise augmentation is the standard strong baseline; pretrain on the BirdCLEF 2021 + 2022 + Xeno-Canto pool before fine-tuning on 2023 species.

The biggest pitfalls are class imbalance — some species have under 10 recordings — and the 2-hour inference budget on the hidden test set. Use focal loss or BCE with class weights, and convert your model to ONNX/TorchScript to fit within the time budget.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Cornell Lab of Ornithology', 'Kaggle', '2023', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/birdclef-2023', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/birdclef-2023/data","format":"OGG audio + CSV metadata"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['audio','classification','bioacoustics','ecology']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-bosch-production-line', 'Bosch Production Line Performance', 'Predict which parts will fail final quality testing on Bosch assembly lines using anonymised numerical, categorical and date measurements taken at every workstation. The data is 14.3 GB and severely imbalanced — failures are roughly 1 in 170 parts.', 'Memory is the first hurdle. Load the numeric file in chunks with pandas, downcast to float32, and immediately drop columns with greater than 99% NaN. XGBoost with histogram method handles the sparsity natively — start there before considering deep models.

The Matthews Correlation Coefficient metric punishes naive accuracy-optimisers. Engineer time-window features from the date file (parts passing through the same station within the same minute often fail together), then chase the famous magic features around consecutive part IDs sharing identical readings — that leak was the difference between top 100 and top 10.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Bosch', 'Kaggle', '2016', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/bosch-production-line-performance', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/bosch-production-line-performance/data","format":"CSV — numeric, categorical, date"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','manufacturing','imbalanced','xgboost']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-web-traffic-forecasting', 'Web Traffic Time Series Forecasting', 'Forecast 60 days of future daily page views for 145,063 Wikipedia articles across multiple languages, access types and agents. Scored on symmetric mean absolute percentage error (SMAPE).', 'Begin with median-by-day-of-week baselines per series — they beat naive ARIMA on most pages because traffic is dominated by weekly seasonality and rare spike events. The winning solution by Arthur Suilin trained a single seq2seq LSTM over all 145k series with cuDNN GRU encoders, conditional on page-level embeddings.

SMAPE is asymmetric near zero — pages with tiny traffic dominate the loss if you predict negatives. Floor predictions at zero, and consider log1p targets. Also watch for the heavy-tailed Wikipedia spider traffic during news events; robust loss (Huber) on log space helps.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/web-traffic-time-series-forecasting', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/web-traffic-time-series-forecasting/data","format":"CSV time series"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['time-series','forecasting','seq2seq','nlp-metadata']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-recruit-restaurant', 'Recruit Restaurant Visitor Forecasting', 'Predict daily visitor counts for hundreds of Japanese restaurants over a future 39-day window using reservation logs from two booking platforms plus weather and holiday data. Evaluated on RMSLE.', 'Join the eight relational files into one long-format frame keyed by restaurant_id × date. Strong public kernels combined LightGBM on engineered lag features (visitor counts 1, 2, 3, 7, 14 days back per restaurant) with a Prophet model per series, then averaged.

Golden Week, Obon and other Japanese holidays cause sharp spikes — encode them explicitly rather than relying on the holiday flag. Validate with a rolling-origin scheme that mimics the public/private split; standard K-fold leaks future information across restaurants that share a chain.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Recruit Holdings', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/recruit-restaurant-visitor-forecasting', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/recruit-restaurant-visitor-forecasting/data","format":"CSV relational"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['time-series','tabular','forecasting','lightgbm']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-openvaccine-mrna', 'OpenVaccine — COVID-19 mRNA Vaccine Degradation Prediction', 'Predict per-nucleotide degradation rates for 6,034 synthetic mRNA constructs designed on the Eterna crowdsourcing platform. Stable mRNA is the bottleneck for distributing COVID-19 vaccines without a cold chain.', 'Inputs come as RNA sequence strings plus computed secondary structure and predicted loop types — convert each construct into a graph where nodes are nucleotides and edges connect both sequential neighbours and base-paired partners. Graph convolutional networks and bidirectional GRUs both score well; the winner combined them.

The public test set has length 107 but the private test set extends to 130 — your model must generalise across lengths. Use position-relative attention rather than absolute embeddings, and train with auxiliary tasks (predicting reactivity at unmeasured positions) for regularisation.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford University, Eterna', 'Kaggle', '2020', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/stanford-covid-vaccine', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/stanford-covid-vaccine/data","format":"JSON sequences + secondary structure"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['medical','bioinformatics','graph-nn','rna']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-liberty-mutual-property', 'Liberty Mutual Group — Property Inspection Prediction', 'Quantify the hazard score of a residential home from 32 anonymised insurance variables, helping route follow-up inspections before binding a policy. This recruiting competition was Liberty Mutual screening for data scientists.', 'Despite anonymisation, simple gradient-boosted trees dominate — XGBoost with about 1000 rounds and tuned eta (0.01–0.02) lands you in the top quarter. Hot-encode the categoricals (they have low cardinality) and let the tree learner discover interactions.

The normalized Gini metric rewards correct ranking, not absolute values — so log-transform the target. Stacking XGBoost with an Extra-Trees regressor on out-of-fold predictions historically gave a meaningful jump.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Liberty Mutual Insurance', 'Kaggle', '2015', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/liberty-mutual-group-property-inspection-prediction', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/liberty-mutual-group-property-inspection-prediction/data","format":"CSV anonymised features"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','insurance','regression','xgboost']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-allstate-claims-severity', 'Allstate Claims Severity', 'Predict the dollar loss associated with each Allstate auto insurance claim from 116 categorical and 14 continuous anonymised features. Roughly 188,000 claims in the training set, evaluated on Mean Absolute Error.', 'MAE is non-differentiable at zero, so XGBoost needs a custom objective — the Fair loss with parameter c around 0.7 is the community-standard approximation. The target is heavy-tailed, so transform y to log(y + 200) before training and invert at inference.

Winning solutions ensembled XGBoost with Keras MLPs trained on label-encoded categoricals. Beware of category cat116 — it has hundreds of levels and naive one-hot blows up memory; use frequency or target encoding instead.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Allstate Insurance', 'Kaggle', '2016', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/allstate-claims-severity', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/allstate-claims-severity/data","format":"CSV"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','insurance','regression','ensemble']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-tensorflow-speech-commands', 'TensorFlow Speech Recognition Challenge', 'Classify one-second utterances of 30 spoken English words from the Google Speech Commands Dataset, predicting 10 target words plus unknown and silence buckets. About 65,000 training clips from thousands of speakers.', 'Convert each WAV to a 40-bin log-mel spectrogram and treat it as a 98×40 image — a small ResNet or Honk-style CNN trains in minutes on a single GPU. Time-shift augmentation (±100 ms) and background-noise mixing from the provided silence files are essential; without them validation accuracy plateaus around 85%.

The trick category is silence — the supplied background tracks must be sliced into one-second windows yourself. Also reserve a held-out set of speakers (not random clips) for validation, because Kaggle''s hidden test set is speaker-disjoint.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google Brain', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/tensorflow-speech-recognition-challenge', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/tensorflow-speech-recognition-challenge/data","format":"WAV files"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['audio','speech','cnn','tensorflow']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-intel-mobileodt-cervical', 'Intel & MobileODT Cervical Cancer Screening', 'Classify cervix images captured on the MobileODT EVA colposcope into three transformation-zone types — Type 1, 2 or 3 — which dictates the appropriate treatment pathway. Real-world clinical screening images from low-resource settings.', 'The dataset is small (≈1500 labelled images plus a noisy additional set) so transfer learning is mandatory. Start with ImageNet-pretrained Inception v3 or ResNet-50; fine-tune only the top blocks first to avoid catastrophic forgetting.

A crucial preprocessing step is cervix localisation — many photos are off-centre with bright speculum reflections. Train a separate U-Net on a few hundred manual bounding-box annotations to crop, then classify the cropped region. Heavy colour-jitter augmentation handles the wide variation in illumination across clinics.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Intel, MobileODT', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/intel-mobileodt-cervical-cancer-screening', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/intel-mobileodt-cervical-cancer-screening/data","format":"JPEG images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['medical','cv','classification','transfer-learning']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-data-science-bowl-2018', '2018 Data Science Bowl — Nuclei Segmentation', 'Find and outline cell nuclei across microscopy images spanning fluorescence stains, brightfield histology, multiple magnifications and several organisms. A two-stage challenge where the second-stage holdout contained completely new acquisition conditions.', 'Treat it as instance segmentation, not semantic. Mask R-CNN (Matterport implementation) was used by 3rd and 5th place teams; the winners combined a U-Net with watershed post-processing over predicted nucleus interior, contour and centre channels.

The domain gap between stages punishes overfit colour distributions — train with aggressive HSV jitter, random invert and stain-normalisation. Evaluate on instance IoU at thresholds 0.5–0.95 in 0.05 steps locally; that matches the leaderboard metric exactly.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Booz Allen Hamilton, Broad Institute', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/data-science-bowl-2018', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/data-science-bowl-2018/data","format":"PNG images + run-length-encoded masks"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['medical','cv','segmentation','u-net']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-state-farm-distracted-driver', 'State Farm Distracted Driver Detection', 'Classify dashboard-camera images of drivers into 10 behaviour classes — safe driving, texting, phone-talking, reaching behind, doing makeup and others. The data spans 26 unique drivers and roughly 22,000 labelled frames.', 'Fine-tune a VGG-16 or ResNet-50 pretrained on ImageNet, freezing the bottom convolutional blocks for the first few epochs. The single most important detail is that train/test splits are driver-disjoint — random K-fold across frames will overestimate accuracy by 15+ percentage points because the same driver appears in many near-duplicate frames.

Use GroupKFold with driver as the group key. Bag predictions over 5 architectures (VGG-16, ResNet-50, Inception v3, Xception, DenseNet) and apply test-time augmentation with horizontal flips and small crops.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'State Farm Insurance', 'Kaggle', '2016', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/state-farm-distracted-driver-detection', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/state-farm-distracted-driver-detection/data","format":"JPEG images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','classification','safety','automotive']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-dogs-vs-cats-redux', 'Dogs vs. Cats Redux — Kernels Edition', 'The classic Asirra dataset relaunched as a Kernels-friendly competition. 25,000 labelled training images of dogs and cats; predict the probability of dog for 12,500 test images. Log-loss evaluation.', 'This is the canonical transfer-learning warm-up. Load Keras'' Xception or ResNet-50 with ImageNet weights, replace the head with a single sigmoid neuron, and fine-tune for 3-5 epochs at lr=1e-4. You should hit 0.04 log-loss easily.

The leaderboard''s top scores below 0.03 require clipping predictions to [0.005, 0.995] — pure log-loss punishes confident wrongs harshly. Also discard the handful of mislabelled training images; community-curated lists exist on the discussion forum.', 'AI/ML', 'beginner', 'Kaggle', 'Kaggle', '2016', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/dogs-vs-cats-redux-kernels-edition', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/dogs-vs-cats-redux-kernels-edition/data","format":"JPEG images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','classification','beginner','transfer-learning']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-plant-seedlings', 'Plant Seedlings Classification', 'Identify the species of a young plant from a top-down RGB image at 10 pixels per mm resolution. 12 weed and crop species — the goal is enabling site-specific herbicide application in precision agriculture.', 'Background subtraction matters more than model choice. HSV-thresholding the green channel removes 90% of the soil and stones, after which a small Inception v3 fine-tuned on the masked crops cracks 0.97 mean F1. Skip the segmentation step and you cap around 0.93.

Class imbalance is mild but real — Small-flowered Cranesbill has 6× more samples than some others. Use class weights in the loss or sample with replacement. Heavy rotation augmentation (full 360°) helps because there is no canonical orientation in the data.', 'AI/ML', 'beginner', 'Aarhus University, University of Southern Denmark', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/plant-seedlings-classification', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/plant-seedlings-classification/data","format":"PNG images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','agriculture','classification','sustainability']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-statoil-iceberg', 'Statoil / C-CORE Iceberg Classifier Challenge', 'Decide whether each satellite SAR chip contains a ship or an iceberg, using two polarisation bands (HH, HV) plus the radar incidence angle. The data comes from Sentinel-1 imagery over iceberg-prone shipping lanes.', 'Stack HH, HV and a third channel (HH+HV, HH-HV, or HH*HV) and feed into a small CNN — the chips are only 75×75. A four-block VGG-style network with batch norm and incidence-angle injection at the dense layer trains in under 10 minutes on a CPU.

Incidence angle has a leak — the public test set has many duplicate angles to the train set; round to one decimal and target-encode as a feature. The most dramatic gains came from pseudo-labelling test images with high-confidence predictions and retraining.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Statoil, C-CORE', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/statoil-iceberg-classifier-challenge', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/statoil-iceberg-classifier-challenge/data","format":"JSON SAR arrays"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','remote-sensing','binary-classification','satellite']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-freesound-audio-tagging-2019', 'Freesound Audio Tagging 2019', 'Multi-label tag 80 everyday sound categories drawn from Google AudioSet ontology using a mix of about 5,000 hand-labelled clips and 20,000 noisy Flickr-sourced clips. Held under the DCASE Challenge umbrella.', 'Compute log-mel spectrograms (128 bins, 44.1 kHz) and treat as multi-label image classification with sigmoid outputs and BCE loss. The winning solution by Roman Sinitsyn used auxiliary classifiers, cyclic-LR schedules and a stacked ensemble of 6 CNN architectures.

The noisy training set is huge but mislabelled — use it for pretraining only, then fine-tune on the clean set. SpecAugment (frequency and time masking) and mixup at the spectrogram level both help. Evaluation is label-weighted label-ranking average precision (lwlrap), so calibrate probabilities across rare classes carefully.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Freesound, Google Research', 'Kaggle', '2019', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/freesound-audio-tagging-2019', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/freesound-audio-tagging-2019/data","format":"WAV audio"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['audio','multi-label','dcase','noisy-labels']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-google-landmark-recognition-2018', 'Google Landmark Recognition Challenge 2018', 'Predict the landmark depicted in each test image from a vocabulary of approximately 15,000 famous places. Training set contains around 1.2 million images, while most test images are distractors that depict no landmark at all.', 'Treat it as both classification and retrieval. Extract DELF local features and compute geometric verification against a database of training images, then rerank with a global descriptor (ResNet-101 with GeM pooling). This two-stage pipeline beat pure classification by a wide margin.

GAP (Global Average Precision) rewards confidence calibration heavily — sort all test predictions by confidence globally, not per-image. Distractor detection is the single largest source of score variance; train a binary landmark-vs-distractor head on a held-out subset to threshold submissions.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google AI', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/landmark-recognition-challenge', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/landmark-recognition-challenge/data","format":"JPEG images + URLs"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','retrieval','fine-grained','large-scale']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-noaa-steller-sea-lions', 'NOAA Fisheries Steller Sea Lion Population Count', 'Count five categories of Steller sea lions — adult males, subadult males, adult females, juveniles, pups — in high-resolution aerial photographs of Aleutian Island rookeries. Helps NOAA monitor an endangered species without burning hundreds of biologist-hours.', 'The labels come as coloured dots on training images, not bounding boxes — extract dot coordinates by colour-thresholding the difference between dotted and undotted versions of each image. The leakage in the ''mismatch'' images (where dotted and original do not align) is documented in the forum and should be cleaned first.

Follow-up: tile each huge image into 300×300 patches and train a regression CNN that predicts a 5-dimensional count vector per patch. Sum patch counts per image at inference. RMSE per class is the metric, so weighting pups (small, hardest) heavier during training pays off.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'NOAA Fisheries', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/noaa-fisheries-steller-sea-lion-population-count', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/noaa-fisheries-steller-sea-lion-population-count/data","format":"JPEG aerial images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','counting','conservation','regression']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-humpback-whale-id', 'Humpback Whale Identification', 'Identify individual humpback whales from photographs of their tail flukes — a fine-grained classification problem with 5,005 unique individuals, most of which have only one or two training images. A new_whale catch-all class adds further ambiguity.', 'Standard cross-entropy fails because of extreme class imbalance and one-shot classes. Use metric learning: triplet loss or ArcFace on a ResNet-50 backbone with a 512-dim embedding, then assign test images via nearest-neighbour in embedding space.

Mask out water and background with a bounding-box detector trained on the supplied fluke-location dataset. Heavy hard-negative mining is essential — 90% of pairs are trivially separable, so without it gradients vanish. Submit a Top-5 ranked list per image; mean average precision at 5 is the metric.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Happywhale', 'Kaggle', '2019', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/humpback-whale-identification', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/humpback-whale-identification/data","format":"JPEG fluke images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','metric-learning','fine-grained','conservation']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-mercedes-benz-greener', 'Mercedes-Benz Greener Manufacturing', 'Predict the seconds a particular Mercedes-Benz configuration spends on the testing bench based on 377 anonymised binary and categorical features representing options like 4WD, air suspension or head-up display. Only 4,209 training rows.', 'Despite the high dimensionality the dataset is tiny, so heavy ensembling overfits. A single well-tuned XGBoost regressor with early stopping on 5-fold CV gets you a fair score; switching to Bayesian ridge on top of PCA-projected features adds the missing variance reduction.

The target has a long tail with one outlier at 265 seconds — winsorise above the 99th percentile during training to stabilise CV. R-squared is the metric, which makes outliers brutal. Stacking XGBoost, LightGBM and a small MLP via a linear meta-learner was the winning formula.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Daimler / Mercedes-Benz', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/mercedes-benz-greener-manufacturing', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/mercedes-benz-greener-manufacturing/data","format":"CSV anonymised features"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','manufacturing','regression','sustainability']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-two-sigma-rental-listings', 'Two Sigma Connect — Rental Listing Inquiries', 'Predict whether a new RentHop rental listing will receive low, medium or high interest based on its photos, description, price, geo-coordinates and amenity tags. A three-class multinomial classification problem.', 'Combine three feature streams: tabular (price, bedrooms, bathrooms, manager and building target encodings), text TF-IDF over description, and image features from a pretrained ResNet over the listing photos. Concatenate and feed into XGBoost for a strong baseline.

Manager_id and building_id leak heavily — a manager who consistently posts high-interest listings is the single most predictive feature. Use leave-one-out target encoding with a small smoothing prior to avoid in-fold leakage. Multinomial log-loss is the metric, so calibrate softmax outputs across folds.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Two Sigma, RentHop', 'Kaggle', '2017', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/two-sigma-connect-rental-listing-inquiries', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/two-sigma-connect-rental-listing-inquiries/data","format":"JSON + image URLs"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','nlp','cv','multimodal','real-estate']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-quickdraw-doodle', 'Quick, Draw! Doodle Recognition Challenge', 'Recognise the category of a hand-drawn doodle from 340 classes using Google''s massive Quick, Draw! game dataset. Inputs come as ordered stroke coordinates with timestamps, not pixel images.', 'You can rasterise strokes to a 256×256 image and train a MobileNetV2 — that gets a respectable baseline. Top solutions instead kept the temporal information: feed stroke sequences into a CNN-LSTM that ingests both the drawn raster and the stroke order indices.

The labels are noisy because players sometimes draw something else then submit; do not chase perfect train accuracy. The metric is MAP@3, so output your top 3 most-likely classes and order them by descending confidence. Memory matters — at 50 million training samples, use a streaming generator and sample uniformly per class each epoch.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google AI', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/quickdraw-doodle-recognition', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/quickdraw-doodle-recognition/data","format":"CSV stroke sequences"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','sequence','large-scale','multi-class']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-avito-demand-prediction', 'Avito Demand Prediction Challenge', 'Predict the deal-probability of a Russian classified-ads listing — a continuous score in [0, 1] indicating likelihood of sale — using title, description, price, region, category, image and historical aggregates. About 1.5 million listings.', 'Stack three independently trained models: a LightGBM on tabular plus aggregated features, a text model (FastText or a small bi-LSTM on Russian tokens), and a CNN over the listing image. Pass out-of-fold predictions of each into a final LightGBM meta-learner.

The deal_probability target is bimodal — many listings score exactly 0 or 1 — so RMSE behaves oddly. Clip predictions to [0.005, 0.995]. Russian text is morphologically rich; lemmatise with pymorphy2 before TF-IDF or you waste vocabulary on word forms.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Avito', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/avito-demand-prediction', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/avito-demand-prediction/data","format":"CSV + images"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','nlp','cv','multimodal','regression']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-talkingdata-adtracking-fraud', 'TalkingData AdTracking Fraud Detection Challenge', 'Detect fraudulent mobile-ad clicks that never result in an app install. The training file contains 200 million click events across IP, device, OS, channel, app and click time — about 0.2% positive class.', '200 million rows will not fit in pandas — use Dask or chunked aggregation to build per-IP, per-device, per-channel click counts at multiple time-windows (next-click delta, clicks in last hour, unique apps per IP). These count features dominate raw categoricals.

LightGBM with histogram method and categorical_feature handling is the standard choice. Subsample negatives aggressively (5-10%) during training and adjust the predicted probabilities at inference. AUC is the metric, so calibration is unimportant — ranking is everything.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'TalkingData', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/talkingdata-adtracking-fraud-detection', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/talkingdata-adtracking-fraud-detection/data","format":"CSV click logs"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','fraud','imbalanced','large-scale']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-santander-customer-transaction', 'Santander Customer Transaction Prediction', 'Predict which Santander bank customers will make a specific transaction in the future from 200 anonymised numerical features. The competition is famous for its synthetic-rows leak that reshaped the leaderboard in the final week.', 'A plain LightGBM on the raw 200 features gets you to around 0.901 AUC. The breakthrough — discovered late — was that the test set contains real and synthetic rows; identifying real ones by looking at value-frequency across the test set lets you build per-feature target-mean encodings that lift AUC to 0.925+.

Do not stack — features are independent given the target (a fact verified empirically), so each feature can be modelled separately and then combined via naive Bayes-style log-odds summation. This is one of the rare competitions where simple statistics beat deep stacks.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Santander Bank', 'Kaggle', '2019', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/santander-customer-transaction-prediction', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/santander-customer-transaction-prediction/data","format":"CSV anonymised features"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','finance','binary-classification','magic-features']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-microsoft-malware-prediction', 'Microsoft Malware Prediction', 'Predict whether a Windows machine will be infected by malware in the near future using telemetry collected by Windows Defender — OS version, antivirus version, processor, region, app inventory and dozens of other categorical fields.', 'Almost every feature is high-cardinality categorical, so target encoding with K-fold smoothing is the workhorse. LightGBM with categorical_feature parameter handles them natively and beats one-hot encoding by a wide margin.

The critical pitfall is temporal drift — public LB and private LB came from different time windows, and many top solutions overfit to public LB through aggressive AvSigVersion and OS-version encoding that became useless on later dates. Validate with a time-based split (sort by AvSigVersion) rather than random K-fold.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Microsoft, Northeastern University', 'Kaggle', '2019', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/microsoft-malware-prediction', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/microsoft-malware-prediction/data","format":"CSV telemetry"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','security','categorical','temporal-drift']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-petfinder-adoption', 'PetFinder.my Adoption Prediction', 'Predict how quickly a pet listed on Malaysia''s PetFinder.my will find a home using tabular metadata (breed, age, colour, fee), free-text descriptions, photos and even audio of the animal. Speed is bucketed into five ordinal classes.', 'This is a true multimodal task — winning kernels combined LightGBM on the structured fields, a sentiment-extracted feature from the description text (the host provided pre-computed Google Cloud NL outputs), and image features from a pretrained DenseNet over the supplied photos.

Quadratic-weighted kappa is the metric, which means class boundaries matter more than raw probabilities. After training a regressor, find optimal integer thresholds on the out-of-fold predictions using scipy.optimize.minimize. Adoption is also imbalanced — rounded categories 0 and 4 are rare.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'PetFinder.my', 'Kaggle', '2019', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/petfinder-adoption-prediction', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/petfinder-adoption-prediction/data","format":"CSV + images + JSON metadata"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','nlp','cv','multimodal','ordinal']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-predict-future-sales-1c', 'Predict Future Sales (1C Company)', 'Forecast next-month total sales for each item × shop combination at one of Russia''s largest software retailers, given 33 months of daily historical sales across 22,000 SKUs and 60 stores. The capstone project of the Coursera How to Win a Data Science Competition course.', 'Convert the daily-sales granularity to monthly aggregates, then build lag features (sales 1, 2, 3, 6, 12 months ago) per shop-item pair plus shop-only and item-only aggregates. The target is the clipped monthly count in [0, 20].

Mean-encoding by shop_id, item_id and item_category_id with K-fold smoothing is the canonical technique taught in the course and remains the strongest signal. LightGBM with early stopping on a hold-out month (October 2015) tracks the public LB closely. Beware of items that appear only in test — they need a sensible fallback (category-average sales).', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', '1C Company', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/competitive-data-science-predict-future-sales', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/competitive-data-science-predict-future-sales/data","format":"CSV time series"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['time-series','tabular','retail','forecasting']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-donorschoose-screening', 'DonorsChoose.org Application Screening', 'Predict whether a US public-school teacher''s project proposal on DonorsChoose will be approved by the platform''s review team. Inputs include four free-text essays, project category, school state, grade level and the teacher''s previous-project count.', 'TF-IDF (character and word n-grams) on the concatenated essays plus a LightGBM on tabular features is the canonical baseline and gets a respectable AUC. The strongest public kernels added pre-trained GloVe embeddings averaged per essay, then concatenated with the LightGBM out-of-fold predictions.

The target is highly imbalanced — about 85% approval rate — so AUC is the right metric and stratified K-fold is mandatory. Watch for teachers who appear in both train and test: their previous-projects count plus prior approval rate becomes a near-perfect feature.', 'AI/ML', 'beginner', 'DonorsChoose.org', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/donorschoose-application-screening', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/donorschoose-application-screening/data","format":"CSV + text"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','nlp','education','binary-classification']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-seti-breakthrough-listen', 'SETI Breakthrough Listen — E.T. Signal Search', 'Detect simulated extraterrestrial narrow-band signals injected into radio spectrograms from the Green Bank Telescope. Each sample is a six-spectrogram cadence alternating on-target and off-target pointings — the signal must appear in only the on-target frames.', 'Stack the three on-target and three off-target spectrograms into a 6-channel image and train EfficientNet-B3 or B5 with binary cross-entropy. Standard ImageNet augmentation hurts; instead use frequency-shift and time-shift augmentation that preserves the on/off cadence structure.

The organisers seeded the signal generator with a specific algorithm; reverse-engineering its statistics from the public training set provided the highest gains. Test-time augmentation with vertical flips (frequency reflection) is safe. AUC is the metric so do not threshold.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Berkeley SETI Research Center', 'Kaggle', '2021', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/seti-breakthrough-listen', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/seti-breakthrough-listen/data","format":"NumPy spectrogram arrays"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','astronomy','signal-processing','binary-classification']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-inclusive-images', 'Inclusive Images Challenge', 'Train a multi-label image classifier on Open Images — predominantly photographs from North America and Europe — that generalises to a stress test set drawn from underrepresented geographic regions. A NeurIPS 2018 competition focused on dataset bias and fairness.', 'Pretraining on the 1.7-million-image Open Images set with focal loss handles the long-tail of 7,178 labels. The shift to the unseen geographic distribution rewards domain-generalisation tricks: mixup, AugMix, and stylisation augmentations that randomise textures while preserving shape.

The public test set is from one geography, the private from another — so any threshold tuning to public LB transfers poorly. Optimise thresholds via class-frequency rebalancing on training data instead. The metric is F2 across labels, so recall is weighted heavier than precision; bias your decision threshold low.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google AI', 'Kaggle', '2018', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/inclusive-images-challenge', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/inclusive-images-challenge/data","format":"JPEG images + multi-label CSV"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cv','fairness','multi-label','domain-generalization','neurips']::text[]),
  ('kaggle-march-madness-analytics-2020', 'Google Cloud & NCAA March Madness Analytics 2020', 'Analytics-style competition (no leaderboard) where Kagglers wrote notebooks telling a data story about the chaos of NCAA Division I basketball tournaments. Released over 40 million play-by-play moments since 2009.', 'This is a writing and visualisation competition more than a modelling one — judges rewarded narratives, clarity and reproducibility. Pick a sharp angle (upset prediction, late-game suspense, bracket entropy) and build a single notebook end-to-end with Plotly or Altair charts.

The winning notebooks built a quantitative definition of madness (lead changes, point-spread volatility, last-lead-change timestamp) and then traced it across years and seeds. Treat your notebook as a long-form Medium article with embedded code; reviewers skim, so lead with the punchline.', 'AI/ML', 'beginner', 'Google Cloud, NCAA', 'Kaggle', '2020', 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/march-madness-analytics-2020', '[{"label":"Competition dataset","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/march-madness-analytics-2020/data","format":"CSV play-by-play"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tabular','analytics','sports','notebook','storytelling']::text[]),
  ('paper-attention-is-all-you-need', 'Reproduce Attention Is All You Need', 'The 2017 paper that replaced recurrence with pure self-attention and birthed every modern LLM. Rebuilding it from scratch — multi-head attention, positional encodings, encoder-decoder stack — is the single best way to internalise how transformers actually work.', 'Pick the original WMT14 English-German task or a smaller proxy like Multi30k so you can train on a single GPU in under a day. Implement the model in PyTorch using only nn.Linear, nn.LayerNorm, and nn.Embedding — no nn.Transformer shortcut. The architectural decision that matters most is scaled dot-product attention and the learning-rate warmup schedule from section 5.3; get those wrong and the model never converges.

Compute budget — the paper trained the base model for 12 hours on 8 P100s. On a single modern GPU expect 1-2 days for a faithful base-size run, or use d_model=256 and 4 heads for a toy version that fits in a Colab session. Start with greedy decode, then add beam search once BLEU stops embarrassing you.

Deliverables — a single train.py under 500 lines, a BLEU-on-newstest2014 number within 2 points of the paper, and an attention-visualisation notebook showing the heads attending to syntactic structure. The visualisation is what separates a parrot reproduction from real understanding.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google Brain', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2017', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.03762', '[{"label":"statmt.org","url":"https://www.statmt.org/wmt14/translation-task.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/attention-is-all-you-need"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/tensorflow/tensor2tensor"},{"label":"nlp.seas.harvard.edu","url":"https://nlp.seas.harvard.edu/annotated-transformer/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','attention','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-resnet-deep-residual', 'Reproduce ResNet — Deep Residual Learning', 'The 2015 paper that solved degradation in very deep networks by adding skip connections, enabling 152-layer ImageNet models. Reproducing ResNet teaches why identity shortcuts work, how BatchNorm interacts with residual paths, and why every modern vision backbone still inherits this trick.', 'Use CIFAR-10 first — the paper itself includes a CIFAR section with ResNet-20/32/56/110 that trains in a few hours on a single GPU. Build the basic block (two 3x3 convs + skip) and the bottleneck block (1x1, 3x3, 1x1) as separate PyTorch modules. The key decision is whether to use the original projection shortcut or the cleaner identity-with-zero-padding variant on dimension changes.

Compute budget — CIFAR ResNet-110 trains in under 6 hours on one consumer GPU. ImageNet ResNet-50 is a 90-epoch, multi-day, multi-GPU commitment — only attempt it if you have access to 4+ GPUs or are willing to use a subset like ImageNet-100.

Deliverables — train a 56-layer model to within 0.5 percent of the 6.97 percent CIFAR-10 error reported, plot training curves for plain-vs-residual to see the degradation phenomenon yourself, then write a one-pager explaining why batch norm before vs after addition changes everything.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Microsoft Research', 'OpenSource', 'CVPR 2016', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1512.03385', '[{"label":"cs.toronto.edu","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html"},{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/deep-residual-learning-for-image-recognition"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/KaimingHe/deep-residual-networks"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cnn','vision','resnet','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-bert-pretraining', 'Reproduce BERT — Bidirectional Pretraining', 'The 2018 paper that made masked-language-model pretraining the default for NLP. Reproducing even a tiny BERT teaches you tokenisation, the MLM + NSP objectives, and why bidirectional context dominates left-to-right LMs for classification.', 'Use a small corpus — WikiText-103 or BookCorpus subset — and a BERT-tiny config (4 layers, 256 hidden, 4 heads). Implement WordPiece tokenisation yourself or borrow Hugging Face tokenizers, then write the MLM data collator that masks 15 percent of tokens with the 80/10/10 strategy from section 3.1. The architectural decision is whether you keep next-sentence-prediction — later work (RoBERTa) showed dropping it actually helps.

Compute budget — full BERT-base required 4 days on 16 TPUs. A from-scratch BERT-tiny on WikiText-103 trains in 12-24 hours on a single modern GPU. Don’t try to match BERT-large numbers without serious hardware — match the recipe instead.

Deliverables — pretrain BERT-tiny, fine-tune on GLUE’s SST-2 or MRPC, and reach within a few points of the published BERT-base scores on those small tasks. The win condition is understanding why fine-tuning a pretrained model beats training from scratch on the same downstream data.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google AI Language', 'OpenSource', 'NAACL 2019', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.04805', '[{"label":"gluebenchmark.com","url":"https://gluebenchmark.com/"},{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/wikitext"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/bert-pre-training-of-deep-bidirectional"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/google-research/bert"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','pretraining','bert']::text[]),
  ('paper-clip-contrastive-language-image', 'Reproduce CLIP — Contrastive Language-Image Pretraining', 'OpenAI’s 2021 paper that trained a joint image-text embedding on 400M web pairs and got zero-shot ImageNet performance comparable to a supervised ResNet-50. Reproducing CLIP teaches contrastive learning at scale, the InfoNCE loss, and how scraped web data can beat curated labels.', 'Use a small open image-text dataset like Conceptual Captions 3M or a 1-2M subset of LAION. Image encoder — a ResNet-50 or ViT-B/32. Text encoder — a small transformer trained from scratch or a frozen DistilBERT. The architectural decision is the temperature parameter in the symmetric contrastive loss — make it learnable and clamp to log(100) like the paper.

Compute budget — the original used 256 V100s for 12 days. A reasonable mini-CLIP on 3M pairs needs 2-4 GPU-days at batch size 1024. Large batches matter for contrastive learning — use gradient accumulation if you only have one GPU.

Deliverables — train your mini-CLIP, then evaluate zero-shot accuracy on CIFAR-100 and a 10-class ImageNet subset. The interesting science is the prompt-engineering ablation — show how ‘a photo of a {label}’ outperforms the raw class word by several points.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'ICML 2021', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2103.00020', '[{"label":"laion.ai","url":"https://laion.ai/blog/laion-400-open-dataset/"},{"label":"ai.google.com","url":"https://ai.google.com/research/ConceptualCaptions/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/learning-transferable-visual-models-from"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/openai/CLIP"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/mlfoundations/open_clip"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['contrastive','vision','nlp','multimodal']::text[]),
  ('paper-vit-vision-transformer', 'Reproduce ViT — Vision Transformer', 'The 2020 paper that proved a pure transformer applied to image patches beats CNNs at scale. Reproducing ViT teaches you patch embedding, why class tokens exist, and why ViT under-performs ResNets on small data but dominates with enough pretraining.', 'Implement patch embedding as a single nn.Conv2d with stride equal to patch size — that is the cleanest way to slice 224x224 images into 16x16 tokens. Add a learnable class token, learnable positional embeddings, and a standard transformer encoder. Start on CIFAR-10 with ViT-Tiny (12 layers, 192 hidden, 3 heads) and patch size 4 since the images are 32x32.

Compute budget — the paper used JFT-300M, which you cannot replicate. The accessible experiment is to train ViT-Small on ImageNet-1k from scratch (1-2 GPU-weeks) or to fine-tune timm’s pretrained ViT-B/16 on a custom dataset and study attention rollout maps. Both teach the right lesson — transformers need either huge data or strong augmentation.

Deliverables — a working ViT under 300 lines, a CIFAR-10 number above 90 percent, and attention-rollout visualisations on a few held-out images. Bonus — repeat the data-scale ablation from the paper to see ViT lose to ResNet at low data and win at high.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google Research', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2021', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2010.11929', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"},{"label":"cs.toronto.edu","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/an-image-is-worth-16x16-words-transformers-1"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/google-research/vision_transformer"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','vision','vit']::text[]),
  ('paper-dinov2-self-supervised-vision', 'Reproduce DINOv2 — Self-Supervised Vision Features', 'Meta’s 2023 paper that scaled self-supervised vision pretraining to produce features that beat supervised models on most downstream tasks without fine-tuning. Reproducing even a small DINOv2 teaches student-teacher distillation, multi-crop augmentation, and how SSL features cluster semantically.', 'Start with the original DINO recipe — it is simpler than DINOv2 and the conceptual core is the same. Use ViT-S/16 as both student and teacher, train on ImageNet-100 or a 200k Open-Images subset. The key trick is the multi-crop strategy — 2 global 224x224 views plus 6 local 96x96 views — and the centering+sharpening on teacher outputs that prevents collapse.

Compute budget — full DINOv2 used 142M images and hundreds of GPUs. A DINO-small reproduction on ImageNet-100 fits in 2-3 GPU-days. The teacher EMA decay (around 0.996) and the temperature schedule are the only knobs you need to tune.

Deliverables — train your DINO, then run k-NN classification on the frozen features for ImageNet-100 val and PCA-visualise the patch features on held-out images. The reveal is that without any labels the features already separate classes — that is the magic the paper is selling.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Meta AI', 'OpenSource', 'TMLR 2024', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.07193', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"},{"label":"storage.googleapis.com","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/openimages/web/index.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/dinov2-learning-robust-visual-features"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/dinov2"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['self-supervised','vision','transformer','ssl']::text[]),
  ('paper-segment-anything-sam', 'Reproduce Segment Anything (SAM)', 'Meta’s 2023 foundation model for promptable image segmentation, trained on 1.1 billion masks. Reproducing a small SAM teaches prompt encoding, mask decoders, and the data-engine flywheel that bootstraps annotation from a partially-trained model.', 'You will not match the 1B-mask dataset, but you can replicate the architecture on COCO or LVIS. The model has three parts — an image encoder (ViT), a prompt encoder for points/boxes/masks, and a lightweight two-layer transformer mask decoder. The architectural lesson is the ambiguity-aware output — predict 3 masks per prompt and a confidence score.

Compute budget — original SAM used 256 A100s for several days. Use a frozen pretrained ViT-B as the image encoder (e.g., MAE or DINOv2 weights) and only train the prompt encoder + mask decoder on COCO. That trims the cost to a few GPU-days.

Deliverables — interactive demo where clicking a point or drawing a box produces a clean mask. Evaluate mIoU on COCO val with point and box prompts. The fun extension is to build a tiny data-engine loop where you label 50 images, train, then use the model to propose masks for 500 more.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Meta AI', 'OpenSource', 'ICCV 2023', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.02643', '[{"label":"cocodataset.org","url":"https://cocodataset.org/"},{"label":"lvisdataset.org","url":"https://www.lvisdataset.org/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/segment-anything"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/segment-anything"},{"label":"ai.meta.com","url":"https://ai.meta.com/datasets/segment-anything/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['segmentation','vision','foundation-model','promptable']::text[]),
  ('paper-nerf-neural-radiance-fields', 'Reproduce NeRF — Neural Radiance Fields', 'The 2020 paper that represented a 3D scene as a tiny MLP queried per-ray, producing photorealistic novel views from a few dozen photos. Reproducing NeRF teaches volumetric rendering, positional encoding for high-frequency signals, and the joy of seeing a 3D scene emerge from gradient descent.', 'Use the original synthetic Lego or Drums dataset — 100 training images with known camera poses. The model is a 9-layer MLP with 256 hidden units; the trick is the sinusoidal positional encoding that lifts (x,y,z,theta,phi) to a 60-D vector so the network can fit high-frequency details. Volumetric rendering is just numerical integration along rays — 64 coarse samples plus 128 fine ones with hierarchical sampling.

Compute budget — the original took 1-2 days per scene on a V100. Modern implementations like instant-ngp or nerfacto train a comparable scene in minutes using hash-grid encodings — but do the slow MLP version first to understand the original. Single consumer GPU is enough.

Deliverables — a render-spiral video of a held-out viewpoint sequence on the Lego scene with PSNR above 30. The follow-up project is to capture 30 phone photos of your room, run COLMAP for poses, and train NeRF on that — the moment your own room renders from a new angle is unforgettable.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'UC Berkeley / Google / UC San Diego', 'OpenSource', 'ECCV 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.08934', '[{"label":"matthewtancik.com","url":"https://www.matthewtancik.com/nerf"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/nerf-representing-scenes-as-neural-radiance"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/bmild/nerf"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/nerfstudio-project/nerfstudio"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['nerf','3d','vision','rendering']::text[]),
  ('paper-ddpm-denoising-diffusion', 'Reproduce DDPM — Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models', 'Ho et al.’s 2020 paper that revived diffusion models and beat GANs on CIFAR-10 image generation. Reproducing DDPM teaches the forward noising process, the reverse denoising parameterisation, and the surprisingly clean simple-MSE training objective that powers every Stable Diffusion model today.', 'Start on CIFAR-10 — 32x32 images mean a single U-Net fits on one GPU. Implement the cosine or linear beta schedule with T=1000 steps, a U-Net with sinusoidal time embeddings injected into each residual block, and train with the simplified L_simple loss (just MSE between predicted and true noise). The architectural decision is whether to predict epsilon, x0, or v — start with epsilon as the paper does.

Compute budget — CIFAR DDPM trains in 1-2 days on a single GPU. Sampling is slow because you must run 1000 reverse steps; once it works, implement DDIM sampling to cut that to 50 steps with negligible quality loss.

Deliverables — FID below 10 on CIFAR-10 unconditional generation, a sampling-progression GIF showing noise resolving into a clean image over 1000 steps, and a comparison of DDIM vs ancestral sampling at different step counts. That last ablation is where most of the practical insight lives.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'UC Berkeley', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.11239', '[{"label":"cs.toronto.edu","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/denoising-diffusion-probabilistic-models"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/hojonathanho/diffusion"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/lucidrains/denoising-diffusion-pytorch"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['diffusion','generative','vision']::text[]),
  ('paper-latent-diffusion-stable', 'Reproduce Latent Diffusion (Mini Stable Diffusion)', 'The 2021 paper behind Stable Diffusion that moved diffusion from pixel space into a learned latent space, slashing compute by 10x while keeping quality. Reproducing a mini LDM teaches VAE compression, classifier-free guidance, and cross-attention conditioning on text.', 'Two stages — first train (or borrow) a KL-regularised VAE that compresses 256x256 images to 32x32x4 latents. Second, train a U-Net diffusion model inside that latent space. For conditioning, cross-attend to CLIP text embeddings. Use a small dataset like CelebA-HQ for unconditional or a 1M LAION subset for text-conditional.

Compute budget — full SD 1.5 took 256 A100s for a month. A mini LDM on CelebA-HQ at 256x256 trains in 3-5 GPU-days. For text-conditional, start by reusing the pretrained SD VAE and only retrain the U-Net — that single change makes the project feasible on one consumer GPU.

Deliverables — generate 256x256 face samples with FID below 15, then add text conditioning and produce a small grid of prompted images. The science deliverable is the classifier-free-guidance ablation — show the quality/diversity trade-off as you sweep the guidance scale from 1 to 15.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'LMU Munich / Runway', 'OpenSource', 'CVPR 2022', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2112.10752', '[{"label":"laion.ai","url":"https://laion.ai/blog/laion-5b/"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/tkarras/progressive_growing_of_gans"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/high-resolution-image-synthesis-with-latent"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/CompVis/latent-diffusion"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/Stability-AI/stablediffusion"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['diffusion','generative','vision','text-to-image']::text[]),
  ('paper-controlnet-conditional', 'Reproduce ControlNet — Conditional Diffusion Control', 'The 2023 paper that added structural controls (edges, depth, pose) to frozen Stable Diffusion via a trainable copy of the encoder with zero-initialised connections. Reproducing ControlNet teaches transfer learning on diffusion models and the brilliantly simple zero-conv trick.', 'Take a pretrained Stable Diffusion 1.5 checkpoint and freeze it. Clone the encoder side of the U-Net into a trainable branch, connect each block back to the frozen decoder through 1x1 conv layers initialised to zero — this is what stops early training noise from breaking the base model. Pick one control modality first: Canny edges, depth maps, or OpenPose skeletons.

Compute budget — original ControlNet trained each condition on 8 A100s for a few days. With a frozen base model and only the control branch trainable, a single 24GB GPU is enough — expect 1-3 days per condition on a 200k-image dataset like a Laion-aesthetics subset preprocessed with Canny or MiDaS.

Deliverables — generate Stable-Diffusion-quality images that follow an input edge or depth map, then build a Gradio demo where users sketch and see the image generate. The follow-up science is sweeping the control-strength parameter and showing the spectrum from ‘control ignored’ to ‘creativity destroyed’.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford', 'OpenSource', 'ICCV 2023', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.05543', '[{"label":"laion.ai","url":"https://laion.ai/blog/laion-aesthetics/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/adding-conditional-control-to-text-to-image"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/lllyasviel/ControlNet"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['diffusion','conditional','vision','controlnet']::text[]),
  ('paper-simclr-contrastive', 'Reproduce SimCLR — Contrastive Visual Representations', 'Chen et al.’s 2020 paper that showed strong data augmentation + a projection head + a big batch is all you need for self-supervised vision. Reproducing SimCLR teaches the NT-Xent loss, why projection heads exist, and why batch size matters for contrastive learning.', 'Use ResNet-50 (or ResNet-18 for a cheaper run) as the encoder, then attach a 2-layer MLP projection head that you discard at evaluation. The augmentation pipeline is the secret sauce — random crop + colour jitter + Gaussian blur + horizontal flip is the minimum. Train on ImageNet or CIFAR-10 with the NT-Xent loss at temperature 0.5.

Compute budget — SimCLR famously needs large batches (4096+) to work well; the original used 128 TPU cores. On a single GPU, use CIFAR-10 with batch size 512 and ResNet-18, or use a 4-GPU setup with batch 1024 on ImageNet-100. Expect 1-3 GPU-days.

Deliverables — train the SSL model, then run linear-probe evaluation (freeze encoder, train a linear classifier on labels) and target a top-1 within a few percent of the paper’s numbers for your config. The interesting ablation is removing the projection head and seeing linear-probe accuracy collapse — that one experiment justifies a whole subfield.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google Brain', 'OpenSource', 'ICML 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2002.05709', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"},{"label":"cs.toronto.edu","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/a-simple-framework-for-contrastive-learning"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/google-research/simclr"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['self-supervised','contrastive','vision','ssl']::text[]),
  ('paper-moco-momentum-contrast', 'Reproduce MoCo — Momentum Contrast', 'He et al.’s 2019 paper that solved the small-batch problem in contrastive learning with a momentum-updated key encoder and a queue of negatives. Reproducing MoCo teaches the dictionary view of contrastive learning and why EMA teachers stabilise SSL training.', 'Use ResNet-50 as both query and key encoders. The key encoder is never directly trained — its weights are an EMA of the query encoder with momentum 0.999. Maintain a queue of 65,536 past keys as negatives. Use the same augmentations as SimCLR but with a much smaller batch (256 is fine).

Compute budget — MoCo v1/v2 trains on ImageNet in roughly 6 GPU-days on 8 GPUs. A single-GPU CIFAR-10 reproduction with ResNet-18 fits in under a day. The point of MoCo is precisely that you do not need SimCLR’s huge batches — verify that by running it at batch 256 and matching SimCLR-batch-4096 numbers on a linear probe.

Deliverables — pretrain MoCo v2, run linear probe, then transfer to a downstream task like Pascal VOC detection and beat a supervised ImageNet pretrain. That detection-transfer win is the canonical proof that SSL features generalise better than supervised ones.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Facebook AI Research', 'OpenSource', 'CVPR 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.05722', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/momentum-contrast-for-unsupervised-visual"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/moco"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['self-supervised','contrastive','vision','ssl']::text[]),
  ('paper-mae-masked-autoencoder', 'Reproduce MAE — Masked Autoencoders', 'He et al.’s 2021 paper that brought BERT-style masked-token pretraining to vision, masking 75 percent of image patches and reconstructing them. Reproducing MAE teaches asymmetric encoder/decoder design and why aggressive masking is actually the easy regime for vision SSL.', 'Use ViT-B/16 as the encoder but only on the visible 25 percent of patches — that is the trick that makes MAE cheap. The decoder is a lightweight transformer (8 layers, 512 hidden) that reconstructs pixel patches with an L2 loss. Train on ImageNet-1k with mask ratio 0.75 and the loss applied only on masked patches.

Compute budget — original MAE pretrained 800-1600 epochs on 64-128 GPUs. A 100-epoch MAE-Base run on ImageNet-100 fits in 2-3 GPU-days. The asymmetric design is what makes this viable — the encoder only sees 25 percent of tokens.

Deliverables — pretrain MAE, fine-tune the encoder on ImageNet-100 classification, and beat a from-scratch ViT trained for the same wall clock. Bonus deliverable — a reconstruction-quality grid showing the model filling in masked regions; it gets eerie when the model invents plausible textures.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Facebook AI Research', 'OpenSource', 'CVPR 2022', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2111.06377', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/masked-autoencoders-are-scalable-vision"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/mae"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['self-supervised','vision','transformer','mae']::text[]),
  ('paper-convnext-2020s', 'Reproduce ConvNeXt — A ConvNet for the 2020s', 'Liu et al.’s 2022 paper that modernised pure ConvNets — depthwise convs, GELU, LayerNorm, inverted bottlenecks — and matched ViTs on ImageNet. Reproducing ConvNeXt is a masterclass in ablation engineering — every design choice is justified with a measurable accuracy delta.', 'Start from a ResNet-50 and apply the modernisations one at a time, just like the paper does — change training recipe, then macro design (stage ratios, patchify stem), then ResNeXt-ify (depthwise), then inverted bottleneck, then 7x7 kernels, then micro choices (LN, GELU, fewer activations). Log accuracy after each change.

Compute budget — full ImageNet-1k training is 300 epochs on 8 GPUs (about a week). Use ImageNet-100 or a Tiny-ImageNet variant to do the same ablation sequence in 1-2 GPU-days per step. The lesson is the methodology, not the absolute number.

Deliverables — a single bar chart with each modernisation as a row and the accuracy gain it produced — your own version of the paper’s headline figure. That chart is more valuable than the final weights.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Facebook AI Research', 'OpenSource', 'CVPR 2022', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.03545', '[{"label":"image-net.org","url":"https://www.image-net.org/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/a-convnet-for-the-2020s"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/ConvNeXt"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cnn','vision','convnext']::text[]),
  ('paper-ppo-proximal-policy', 'Reproduce PPO — Proximal Policy Optimization', 'Schulman et al.’s 2017 paper that made on-policy RL practical with a clipped surrogate objective. Reproducing PPO teaches actor-critic methods, GAE advantage estimation, and the dozens of small implementation details that the original paper omitted but every working PPO has.', 'Pick a few classic control environments first — CartPole, LunarLander, then a MuJoCo task like HalfCheetah or Hopper. Implement a shared-trunk actor-critic network, run multiple parallel environments to collect rollouts, compute GAE advantages with lambda=0.95, and train with the clipped objective at epsilon=0.2 for 10 epochs per rollout.

Compute budget — PPO is CPU-bound for control tasks; a single laptop can solve CartPole in minutes and MuJoCo Hopper in a few hours. Read the ‘37 implementation details of PPO’ blog post by Costa Huang before you start — it will save you a week of mysterious instability.

Deliverables — learning curves on 3+ environments compared to a baseline like Stable-Baselines3, plus a write-up of which of the 37 details you turned off and how badly each broke training. That ablation is the actual content of the project.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'arXiv 2017', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.06347', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/proximal-policy-optimization-algorithms"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/openai/baselines"},{"label":"iclr-blog-track.github.io","url":"https://iclr-blog-track.github.io/2022/03/25/ppo-implementation-details/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rl','policy-gradient','ppo']::text[]),
  ('paper-dqn-atari', 'Reproduce DQN — Playing Atari with Deep RL', 'Mnih et al.’s 2013 paper that learned to play Atari games from raw pixels using Q-learning + a CNN + experience replay. Reproducing DQN teaches the bellman update, replay buffers, target networks, and why naive deep Q-learning diverges without these stabilisers.', 'Use the Arcade Learning Environment via gymnasium with the standard Atari wrappers — 84x84 grayscale, frame stack of 4, no-op resets, sticky actions. Implement a 3-conv-layer Q-network, an Adam optimiser, a 1M-transition replay buffer, and a target network updated every 10k steps. Start with a single easy game like Pong or Breakout.

Compute budget — Pong solves in 1-2 hours on one GPU. Breakout takes 8-24 hours. The original 50M-frame regime on harder games like Seaquest takes days. You do not need a fancy GPU — Atari is small enough that a laptop GPU works.

Deliverables — reach human-level on Pong and Breakout, plot training curves, then add Double-DQN, Dueling-DQN, and Prioritised Replay one at a time to reproduce the Rainbow ablation in miniature. That is the cleanest survey-as-project you can do in deep RL.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'DeepMind', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS Workshop 2013', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.5602', '[{"label":"gymlibrary.dev","url":"https://www.gymlibrary.dev/environments/atari/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/playing-atari-with-deep-reinforcement"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/google/dopamine"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rl','dqn','q-learning','atari']::text[]),
  ('paper-muzero-mastering-atari', 'Reproduce MuZero — Mastering Atari, Go, Chess by Planning', 'Schrittwieser et al.’s 2019 paper that combined Monte Carlo Tree Search with a learned model of the environment dynamics, removing AlphaZero’s requirement of perfect simulators. Reproducing MuZero teaches model-based RL, MCTS at scale, and the brilliant trick of learning a model in latent-reward-value space rather than pixel space.', 'Start on a toy environment — CartPole or a small grid world — to debug MCTS and the three networks (representation, dynamics, prediction). The model is not trained to reconstruct observations; it is trained so that rolling forward in latent space matches the true value and reward sequences. That insight is the heart of the paper.

Compute budget — original MuZero trained for weeks on TPU pods. The accessible target is the muzero-general open-source implementation on CartPole/LunarLander (hours) or a single Atari game with massive simplifications (days). Do not attempt full Atari MuZero without serious compute.

Deliverables — MuZero beating tabular Q-learning on CartPole, then a write-up of how the latent dynamics model differs from world-model approaches like Dreamer. Bonus — visualise the MCTS tree for a few interesting states and show how the planner explores.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'DeepMind', 'OpenSource', 'Nature 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.08265', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/mastering-atari-go-chess-and-shogi-by"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/werner-duvaud/muzero-general"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rl','model-based','mcts','alphazero']::text[]),
  ('paper-world-models-ha-schmidhuber', 'Reproduce World Models (Ha & Schmidhuber)', 'The 2018 paper that trained a VAE to compress observations, an RNN to predict next-latents, and then trained a tiny policy entirely inside the learned dream — solving CarRacing without ever taking a real gradient through the environment. Reproducing it teaches model-based RL and dream-policy training.', 'Three independent stages — first train a VAE on random-policy frames from CarRacing-v2 to get a 32-D latent. Second, train an MDN-RNN on rollouts of latents + actions to predict the next latent. Third, train a tiny controller (a few hundred parameters) using CMA-ES, running the policy inside the dreamed RNN rollout rather than the real env. Combine and evaluate in the real env.

Compute budget — full pipeline is single-GPU friendly and runs in 1-2 days. The CMA-ES step is CPU-parallel and benefits from many cores. This is the smallest-compute model-based RL paper that still teaches the full pattern.

Deliverables — solve CarRacing-v2 to 800+ average reward, then make a video of the dream rollouts side-by-side with the real environment — they should look similar enough that you trust the controller learned a useful policy in the dream.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google Brain / IDSIA', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2018', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.10122', '[{"label":"gymlibrary.dev","url":"https://www.gymlibrary.dev/environments/box2d/car_racing/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/world-models"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/hardmaru/WorldModelsExperiments"},{"label":"worldmodels.github.io","url":"https://worldmodels.github.io/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rl','model-based','vae','world-models']::text[]),
  ('paper-t5-text-to-text', 'Reproduce T5 — Text-to-Text Transfer Transformer', 'Raffel et al.’s 2019 paper that unified every NLP task into text-in-text-out and ran a massive ablation of pretraining choices. Reproducing T5 — even a tiny version — teaches the encoder-decoder transformer, span-corruption pretraining, and the value of one architecture for translation, QA, summarisation, and classification.', 'Train T5-tiny (3M params) on a C4 subset of a few GB. Implement span-corruption masking — pick non-overlapping spans averaging 3 tokens, replace each with a sentinel, predict the spans. The encoder is bidirectional, the decoder is autoregressive with cross-attention. Use relative position biases instead of absolute embeddings.

Compute budget — T5-base on full C4 took weeks on a TPU pod. T5-tiny on C4-10G is a few GPU-days. Don’t chase headline T5-XXL numbers; the goal is to learn the recipe.

Deliverables — pretrained T5-tiny, then fine-tune on 3 tasks (summarisation on XSum, classification on SST-2, simple QA on SQuAD) with the unified text-to-text format. The interesting science is which task benefits most from larger pretraining compute — usually the answer surprises people.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Google Research', 'OpenSource', 'JMLR 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.10683', '[{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/c4"},{"label":"gluebenchmark.com","url":"https://gluebenchmark.com/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/exploring-the-limits-of-transfer-learning"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/google-research/text-to-text-transfer-transformer"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','t5','encoder-decoder']::text[]),
  ('paper-roberta-robust-bert', 'Reproduce RoBERTa — Robustly Optimised BERT', 'Liu et al.’s 2019 paper that showed BERT was significantly undertrained and beat it with longer training, bigger batches, more data, dynamic masking, and no next-sentence-prediction. Reproducing RoBERTa teaches that recipes often matter more than architectures.', 'Start from your BERT-tiny code (if you reproduced BERT first) and change five things one at a time — drop NSP, use dynamic masking (re-mask each epoch), increase batch size to 8k via gradient accumulation, train for 4-10x longer, and use a larger byte-level BPE tokeniser. Measure GLUE after each change.

Compute budget — full RoBERTa-base trained 8 days on 1024 GPUs. A tiny-RoBERTa on a 10G text corpus is a 3-5 GPU-day project on one GPU. The point is the ablation methodology — show which of the five changes contributed what.

Deliverables — RoBERTa-tiny outperforming your BERT-tiny by several GLUE points, with a per-change attribution chart. That chart is the deliverable that matters — it teaches you that papers often improve over baselines for boring training-config reasons rather than architectural ones.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Facebook AI', 'OpenSource', 'arXiv 2019', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1907.11692', '[{"label":"gluebenchmark.com","url":"https://gluebenchmark.com/"},{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/wikitext"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/roberta-a-robustly-optimized-bert-pretraining"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/fairseq"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','roberta','pretraining']::text[]),
  ('paper-gpt2-language-models', 'Reproduce GPT-2 from Scratch (nanoGPT-style)', 'Karpathy’s nanoGPT made reproducing GPT-2 a rite of passage for ML engineers. The original 2019 GPT-2 paper showed a decoder-only transformer could perform multi-task NLP zero-shot just by training on enough internet text. Reproducing it teaches autoregressive language modelling end-to-end.', 'Build a decoder-only transformer — causal self-attention, layernorm pre-norm, GELU. Tokenise with tiktoken’s GPT-2 BPE. Train on OpenWebText (an open replica of GPT-2’s WebText). Start with the 124M-parameter ‘small’ config — 12 layers, 768 hidden, 12 heads, context 1024.

Compute budget — Karpathy’s nanoGPT reproduces GPT-2-124M in about 4 days on 8 A100s, or roughly 24-48 hours on a single H100. On consumer hardware target the 10M-parameter ‘Shakespeare’ config first (trains in minutes), then scale up. The model is so simple that the entire codebase fits in 300 lines.

Deliverables — validation loss matching the GPT-2-124M curve, plus a sampling demo that produces coherent paragraphs. The follow-up project is to swap in FlashAttention and measure the throughput improvement — it teaches that systems improvements increasingly matter more than architecture changes.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'OpenAI Blog 2019', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.14165', '[{"label":"skylion007.github.io","url":"https://skylion007.github.io/OpenWebTextCorpus/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/language-models-are-few-shot-learners"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/karpathy/nanoGPT"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/openai/gpt-2"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','gpt','language-model']::text[]),
  ('paper-llama-foundation-models', 'Reproduce LLaMA — Open Foundation Language Models', 'Meta’s 2023 paper showed that careful training on public data produces a 7B model that beats much larger LLMs. Reproducing a tiny LLaMA teaches RMSNorm, SwiGLU, rotary positional embeddings, and the architectural choices behind every modern open-weight LLM.', 'The architecture is decoder-only transformer with three modern swaps versus GPT-2 — RMSNorm instead of LayerNorm, SwiGLU instead of GELU MLP, and RoPE instead of learned position embeddings. Train on a deduplicated subset of The Pile or RedPajama. Start with a 100M-parameter config to debug the pipeline.

Compute budget — LLaMA-7B used 1.4T tokens on 2048 A100s for 21 days. A 100-300M LLaMA on 10-50B tokens fits in 1-2 weeks on a single 8-GPU node, or much less if you accept undertraining. Pay attention to FlashAttention and bf16 mixed precision; without them you will be too slow to converge.

Deliverables — pretrained LLaMA-tiny, then fine-tune with LoRA on an instruction dataset like Alpaca and produce a usable assistant. The instructive comparison is your-tiny-LLaMA versus your-equally-sized-GPT-2 — every modern arch change should give a measurable perplexity gain.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Meta AI', 'OpenSource', 'arXiv 2023', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.13971', '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/togethercomputer/RedPajama-Data"},{"label":"pile.eleuther.ai","url":"https://pile.eleuther.ai/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/llama-open-and-efficient-foundation-language"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/llama"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/karpathy/llama2.c"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['transformer','nlp','llama','language-model']::text[]),
  ('paper-instructgpt-rlhf', 'Reproduce InstructGPT — RLHF Pipeline', 'Ouyang et al.’s 2022 paper that turned GPT-3 into ChatGPT by combining supervised fine-tuning, a reward model trained on human preferences, and PPO. Reproducing the full RLHF stack teaches reward modelling, KL-controlled policy optimisation, and the gotchas behind every aligned LLM.', 'Three stages — SFT on a prompt+response dataset (use Anthropic HH-RLHF or OpenAssistant); reward model — train a classification head on preference pairs to score ‘which response is better’; PPO with a KL penalty to the SFT model so the policy does not drift. Use TRL or trlx as a reference but implement the loss yourself once to understand it.

Compute budget — full InstructGPT used GPT-3 175B; you should use a 1B-7B base like Pythia or LLaMA-tiny. End-to-end on a single 24GB GPU is feasible with LoRA on all three stages and takes 2-5 GPU-days. Without LoRA you need an 8-GPU node.

Deliverables — base SFT model versus RLHF model evaluated by an LLM judge or simple human A/B test on held-out prompts. The KL-divergence plot during PPO is the diagnostic that tells you if alignment is happening or if the model is reward-hacking; capture it.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2022', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.02155', '[{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/Anthropic/hh-rlhf"},{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/OpenAssistant/oasst1"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/training-language-models-to-follow"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/huggingface/trl"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/CarperAI/trlx"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rlhf','nlp','alignment','ppo']::text[]),
  ('paper-lora-low-rank', 'Reproduce LoRA — Low-Rank Adaptation', 'Hu et al.’s 2021 paper that fine-tunes large models by injecting trainable low-rank matrices into linear layers, freezing the original weights. Reproducing LoRA teaches parameter-efficient fine-tuning and why a rank-8 update can match full fine-tuning quality for many tasks.', 'For each target linear layer (typically attention Q and V), replace forward(x) = Wx with forward(x) = Wx + alpha/r * B @ A @ x where A is rank-r-by-d initialised randomly and B is d-by-rank-r initialised to zero. Freeze W. That zero init is what makes training stable from step 0. Pick a 1-3B base model (Pythia, OPT, LLaMA-tiny) and an instruction dataset.

Compute budget — LoRA fine-tuning of a 7B model fits on a single 24GB consumer GPU; a 1B model fits on 8GB. Sweep rank in {1, 4, 8, 16, 64} and full-fine-tune as a baseline. Each run is hours, not days.

Deliverables — a plot of downstream accuracy vs trainable-parameter count, showing LoRA-rank-8 matching or beating full fine-tuning at 1000x fewer trainable params. Bonus — implement DoRA or QLoRA for a comparison; the QLoRA story (4-bit base + LoRA) is what makes 70B models trainable on one GPU.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Microsoft', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2022', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.09685', '[{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/datasets/tatsu-lab/alpaca"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/lora-low-rank-adaptation-of-large-language"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/microsoft/LoRA"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/huggingface/peft"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['fine-tuning','lora','peft','nlp']::text[]),
  ('paper-rag-retrieval-augmented', 'Reproduce RAG — Retrieval-Augmented Generation', 'Lewis et al.’s 2020 paper that combined a dense retriever (DPR) with a generator (BART) so the model can look things up at inference time. Reproducing RAG teaches embeddings, vector search, and the difference between parametric and non-parametric knowledge.', 'Two components — retriever and generator. Retriever: encode Wikipedia passages with a sentence-transformer like bge-small or e5-small, store in FAISS. Generator: take a small encoder-decoder (Flan-T5-small or BART-base), prepend top-k retrieved passages to the query, fine-tune on Natural Questions or TriviaQA. End-to-end training (joint retriever + generator) is the harder version; start with frozen retriever.

Compute budget — frozen-retriever RAG is small — a single GPU and an afternoon. Joint training requires periodically re-indexing the corpus and is meaningfully harder; a few GPU-days. Wikipedia indexed at the paragraph level is roughly 21M passages and fits in a few GB on disk.

Deliverables — exact-match accuracy on Natural Questions or TriviaQA dev set beating a closed-book baseline of the same generator size. The interesting plot is accuracy versus k (number of retrieved passages) — the curve usually plateaus surprisingly fast, which informs every production RAG design.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Facebook AI Research', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2020', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.11401', '[{"label":"ai.google.com","url":"https://ai.google.com/research/NaturalQuestions"},{"label":"nlp.cs.washington.edu","url":"https://nlp.cs.washington.edu/triviaqa/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/retrieval-augmented-generation-for-knowledge"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/facebookresearch/DPR"},{"label":"huggingface.co","url":"https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/model_doc/rag"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['nlp','retrieval','rag','qa']::text[]),
  ('paper-react-reasoning-acting', 'Reproduce ReAct — Reasoning + Acting Agents', 'Yao et al.’s 2022 paper that interleaved chain-of-thought reasoning with tool actions, letting LLM agents do multi-step QA via search and calculator calls. Reproducing ReAct teaches prompt-driven tool use and the building blocks behind every modern agentic LLM framework.', 'Pick an LLM you can call (a local Llama-3-8B-Instruct via Ollama is enough). Define two tools — a Wikipedia search action and a lookup action. Few-shot the model with the ReAct trajectory format: Thought / Action / Observation triplets repeated until ‘Finish[answer]’. Evaluate on HotpotQA dev set.

Compute budget — inference-only project, no training needed. CPU + a hosted or local LLM is fine; expect a few hours of API calls or local generation. The intellectually load-bearing work is in prompt design and parser robustness, not GPU time.

Deliverables — ReAct outperforming a chain-of-thought-only baseline on HotpotQA by at least 5 EM points, plus an error-analysis bucket of where the agent fails (usually loops, malformed actions, or hallucinated tool outputs). Bonus — extend to a tool the paper didn’t use, like a Python REPL, and benchmark on GSM8K.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Princeton / Google Brain', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2023', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629', '[{"label":"hotpotqa.github.io","url":"https://hotpotqa.github.io/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/react-synergizing-reasoning-and-acting-in"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/ysymyth/ReAct"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['agents','nlp','tool-use','react']::text[]),
  ('paper-yolov3-object-detection', 'Reproduce YOLOv3 — Real-Time Object Detection', 'Redmon & Farhadi’s 2018 detector that ran object detection in a single forward pass with multi-scale predictions. Reproducing YOLOv3 teaches anchor boxes, IoU-based losses, non-max suppression, and how a one-stage detector trades a bit of accuracy for huge speed.', 'Use COCO 2017 train (118k images) or, if compute is tight, Pascal VOC (16k). The model is a Darknet-53 backbone plus three detection heads at strides 8, 16, 32. Each head predicts anchor offsets, objectness, and class scores for 3 anchors. The loss combines binary cross-entropy for objectness and class, plus regression for boxes.

Compute budget — COCO YOLOv3 trains in 2-4 days on a 4-GPU node, or use ultralytics’ yolov3 as a reference. On a single GPU, train on Pascal VOC instead — it fits in a day. Implement NMS yourself the first time; it teaches you what a detection actually is.

Deliverables — mAP within a couple of points of the paper on your chosen dataset, a webcam demo running at 30+ FPS, and an ablation showing what happens when you remove one of the three detection scales — usually small objects collapse.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'University of Washington', 'OpenSource', 'arXiv 2018', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.02767', '[{"label":"cocodataset.org","url":"https://cocodataset.org/"},{"label":"host.robots.ox.ac.uk","url":"http://host.robots.ox.ac.uk/pascal/VOC/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/yolov3-an-incremental-improvement"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['vision','detection','yolo']::text[]),
  ('paper-unet-segmentation', 'Reproduce U-Net — Biomedical Image Segmentation', 'Ronneberger et al.’s 2015 paper that introduced the encoder-decoder with skip connections that still dominates segmentation and is the backbone of every diffusion model. Reproducing U-Net teaches per-pixel prediction, data augmentation for tiny datasets, and the elegance of symmetric skip connections.', 'The architecture is 4 downsampling blocks (conv-conv-maxpool), a bottleneck, 4 upsampling blocks (transposed-conv + concat-with-skip + conv-conv). Start with a simple segmentation task — Carvana car segmentation, Oxford Pets, or the original ISBI 2012 EM dataset that the paper uses. Loss is binary cross-entropy plus optionally Dice.

Compute budget — small. A 256x256 U-Net trains in an hour or two on a single GPU even on Carvana. Heavy augmentation (elastic deformations, random crops, flips) matters more than depth.

Deliverables — mIoU above 0.92 on Carvana val, plus side-by-side input/prediction/ground-truth visualisations. Once it works, swap the encoder for a pretrained ResNet-34 (a ‘U-ResNet’) and measure the gain on a small medical dataset — that one experiment is the canonical motivation for transfer learning in segmentation.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'University of Freiburg', 'OpenSource', 'MICCAI 2015', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1505.04597', '[{"label":"kaggle.com","url":"https://www.kaggle.com/c/carvana-image-masking-challenge"},{"label":"robots.ox.ac.uk","url":"https://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~vgg/data/pets/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/u-net-convolutional-networks-for-biomedical"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/milesial/Pytorch-UNet"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['vision','segmentation','unet','medical']::text[]),
  ('paper-gan-goodfellow', 'Reproduce GAN — Generative Adversarial Networks', 'Goodfellow et al.’s 2014 paper that framed generative modelling as a two-player minimax game between a generator and a discriminator. Reproducing the original GAN teaches the joys and pains of adversarial training — mode collapse, oscillation, hyperparameter brittleness — and motivates every stability fix that followed.', 'Start on MNIST — that is what the original paper used. Generator: 4-layer MLP from a 100-D noise vector to a 28x28 image. Discriminator: 4-layer MLP from image to a scalar. Train with alternating gradient steps on the BCE-with-logits loss. Then move to a DCGAN (convolutional) on CIFAR-10 or CelebA.

Compute budget — MNIST GAN trains in minutes on a CPU. DCGAN on 64x64 CelebA fits in a few hours on one GPU. This is the cheapest ‘get a taste of generative modelling’ project you can do.

Deliverables — a generated-samples grid at multiple training milestones (epoch 1, 10, 50, 100) showing the progression from noise to faces. Then deliberately induce mode collapse by training the discriminator too aggressively, capture the failure mode, and show how feature matching or label smoothing rescues it. Failure analysis is the whole point of this project.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'University of Montreal', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2014', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1406.2661', '[{"label":"yann.lecun.com","url":"http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/mnist/"},{"label":"mmlab.ie.cuhk.edu.hk","url":"https://mmlab.ie.cuhk.edu.hk/projects/CelebA.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/generative-adversarial-networks"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/goodfeli/adversarial"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['generative','gan','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-vae-kingma-welling', 'Reproduce VAE — Variational Autoencoder', 'Kingma & Welling’s 2013 paper that combined autoencoders with variational inference, giving you a generative latent-variable model trained with stochastic gradient descent. Reproducing VAE teaches the ELBO, the reparameterisation trick, and KL-vs-reconstruction trade-offs that resurface in every modern latent generative model.', 'MNIST VAE — encoder MLP outputs mu and log-sigma of a 20-D Gaussian latent, decoder MLP maps z back to a Bernoulli image. Loss is reconstruction BCE plus KL to a standard normal. The reparameterisation trick — z = mu + sigma * epsilon where epsilon is iid Gaussian — is the entire point; understand why it makes the gradient pass through.

Compute budget — trivial. Minutes on a CPU, seconds on a GPU. Then move to a convolutional VAE on CelebA at 64x64 (a few GPU-hours) and finally a beta-VAE to see disentanglement.

Deliverables — generated samples by sampling z from N(0, I) and decoding, plus a 2D latent-space traversal (train with 2D z and grid the latent) showing smooth interpolation between digit classes. The traversal is the canonical visualisation; recreate it and you know your VAE works.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'University of Amsterdam', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2014', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.6114', '[{"label":"yann.lecun.com","url":"http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/mnist/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/auto-encoding-variational-bayes"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/AntixK/PyTorch-VAE"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['generative','vae','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-adam-optimizer', 'Reproduce Adam — Adaptive Moment Estimation', 'Kingma & Ba’s 2014 optimiser combining momentum (first moment) and RMSProp (second moment) with bias correction. Reproducing Adam from scratch teaches optimisation under the hood and reveals exactly why it is the default optimiser despite well-known generalisation quirks.', 'Implement Adam in 30 lines — maintain exponentially-decayed first and second moment estimates m and v, bias-correct them by dividing by (1 - beta^t), then update params with lr * m_hat / (sqrt(v_hat) + eps). Compare on three tasks — a noisy quadratic, MNIST MLP, and CIFAR-10 ResNet — against vanilla SGD, SGD+momentum, and RMSProp.

Compute budget — minimal. A laptop is enough. The intellectual content is in the analysis, not the compute.

Deliverables — a single chart comparing convergence curves of SGD, SGD+momentum, RMSProp, Adam, and AdamW on the three tasks. Then write a one-page note on the Reddi-et-al ‘On the Convergence of Adam’ result — Adam can fail to converge in pathological cases that AMSGrad fixes — and reproduce the toy counterexample. Understanding when your default optimiser fails is genuinely useful.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'University of Toronto / OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2015', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1412.6980', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/adam-a-method-for-stochastic-optimization"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['optimisation','adam','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-batch-normalization', 'Reproduce Batch Normalization', 'Ioffe & Szegedy’s 2015 paper that accelerated deep network training by normalising activations per mini-batch. Reproducing BN teaches the train-vs-eval semantics that trip up half of all PyTorch beginners, and motivates the LayerNorm/GroupNorm/InstanceNorm family.', 'Implement BatchNorm from scratch — per-channel mean and variance over the batch dimension during training, running averages used at evaluation, plus learnable affine parameters gamma and beta. Compare on a small CNN with and without BN — train loss, eval loss, and tolerance to large learning rates.

Compute budget — minimal, one GPU, a few hours. The science is the ablation.

Deliverables — three plots: (1) train loss curves with BN at lr=0.01 vs no BN at lr=0.01 — the no-BN run diverges, (2) max trainable learning rate with vs without BN, (3) a comparison of BN, LayerNorm, GroupNorm, InstanceNorm on the same model. The third plot is what teaches you when each norm is appropriate — BN dominates vision CNNs, LayerNorm dominates transformers, GroupNorm wins at tiny batch sizes.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Google', 'OpenSource', 'ICML 2015', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1502.03167', '[{"label":"cs.toronto.edu","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/batch-normalization-accelerating-deep"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['normalisation','foundational','training']::text[]),
  ('paper-bahdanau-attention', 'Reproduce Bahdanau Attention — NMT with Alignment', 'Bahdanau, Cho & Bengio’s 2014 paper that introduced attention to neural machine translation, replacing the fixed-length-vector bottleneck of encoder-decoder RNNs. Reproducing it teaches the original additive attention mechanism — the conceptual ancestor of every transformer.', 'Use a small bilingual dataset like Multi30k (English-German, 30k pairs). Encoder — a bidirectional GRU. Decoder — a GRU with an attention module that scores every encoder hidden state against the current decoder state using a learned MLP (the additive/Bahdanau form). Soft-attend, then feed the context vector to the decoder.

Compute budget — small. Multi30k trains in a few hours on a single GPU. The point is to internalise attention before transformers.

Deliverables — BLEU on Multi30k test plus alignment-heatmap visualisations for a few sentences — you should clearly see the model attending to source words in roughly the right order. That heatmap is the single best image in the history of NLP and the reason Vaswani et al. could pitch ‘Attention is all you need’ three years later.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Universite de Montreal', 'OpenSource', 'ICLR 2015', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1409.0473', '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/multi30k/dataset"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/neural-machine-translation-by-jointly"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['nlp','attention','translation','foundational']::text[]),
  ('paper-trpo-trust-region', 'Reproduce TRPO — Trust Region Policy Optimization', 'Schulman et al.’s 2015 paper that introduced monotonic-improvement guarantees for policy gradient methods via a KL-divergence trust region. Reproducing TRPO is harder than PPO and teaches conjugate gradients, Fisher-vector products, and exactly why PPO became the practical replacement.', 'Implement vanilla policy gradient with GAE first to get a baseline. Then add the trust-region step — compute the policy gradient, then use conjugate gradient on the Fisher information matrix (via Hessian-vector products on the KL) to solve for the natural gradient direction, then line-search to satisfy the KL constraint. Test on MuJoCo Hopper or Walker2d.

Compute budget — TRPO is CPU-light, GPU-light, and gradient-step-light per environment step. A single laptop solves CartPole and most easy MuJoCo tasks in hours. The complexity is implementation, not compute.

Deliverables — TRPO matching PPO on 3 MuJoCo tasks within reasonable wall clock, plus a writeup explaining the conjugate-gradient step in your own words. Bonus deliverable — a head-to-head wall-clock-vs-PPO chart that justifies why PPO won in practice despite weaker theoretical guarantees.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'UC Berkeley / OpenAI', 'OpenSource', 'ICML 2015', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/1502.05477', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/trust-region-policy-optimization"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/openai/baselines"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['rl','policy-gradient','trpo']::text[]),
  ('paper-tree-of-thoughts', 'Reproduce Tree of Thoughts — Deliberate LLM Reasoning', 'Yao et al.’s 2023 paper that lets an LLM explore a tree of partial ‘thoughts’ with self-evaluation and search rather than a single chain. Reproducing ToT teaches LLM-as-a-search-process, beam/BFS over generations, and how planning lifts the same base model on Game of 24 from 4 percent to 74 percent.', 'Pick Game of 24 (given 4 numbers, reach 24 using arithmetic) as the canonical task — the paper reports a dramatic jump there. Implement four functions — thought generation, state evaluation (LLM rates each partial as sure/maybe/impossible), search (BFS at width 5), and termination. Use any local instruct LLM via the OpenAI-compatible API.

Compute budget — inference-only, no training. Each Game of 24 instance takes a few dozen LLM calls; budget hours-not-days of API or local-LLM time. The exercise is engineering and prompt design.

Deliverables — accuracy on the Game of 24 test set significantly above chain-of-thought on the same base LLM, plus a visualisation of an example search tree showing which branches got pruned. Bonus — extend to Creative Writing or Crosswords from the paper and measure how the search width vs depth trade-off changes.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Princeton / Google DeepMind', 'OpenSource', 'NeurIPS 2023', 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.10601', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"paperswithcode.com","url":"https://paperswithcode.com/paper/tree-of-thoughts-deliberate-problem-solving"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/princeton-nlp/tree-of-thought-llm"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['agents','nlp','reasoning','search']::text[]),
  ('paper-raft-consensus', 'Reproduce Raft — Understandable Consensus', 'Ongaro & Ousterhout’s 2014 paper that decomposed consensus into leader election, log replication, and safety — finally giving systems engineers a Paxos alternative they could actually implement. Reproducing Raft teaches distributed systems first-principles — RPC, persistent state, partial failures, and the joy of debugging split-brain.', 'Pick a language with good async/RPC support — Go is canonical (it is what etcd uses), Rust if you like pain, Python with asyncio if you want speed of iteration. Implement the three sub-problems in order — leader election with randomised election timeouts (figure 2 in the paper), log replication with AppendEntries, then snapshotting (section 7) once the basics work. Persist currentTerm, votedFor, and log to disk before every RPC.

Compute budget — none. Run 3 or 5 processes on your laptop. The hard part is test infrastructure — write a partition-injecting harness that drops messages between random pairs of nodes and asserts linearisability after recovery. The MIT 6.824 labs are the gold-standard set of tests; use them.

Deliverables — a key-value store on top of your Raft that survives MIT-6.824-lab-3 unreliable network tests. Then write a blog post about the bug that took you longest — there is always one, usually around leader-completeness when a fresh leader inherits an uncommitted log entry.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford', 'OpenSource', 'USENIX ATC 2014', 'https://raft.github.io/raft.pdf', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"raft.github.io","url":"https://raft.github.io/"},{"label":"pdos.csail.mit.edu","url":"https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.824/"},{"label":"usenix.org","url":"https://www.usenix.org/conference/atc14/technical-sessions/presentation/ongaro"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','distributed','consensus','raft']::text[]),
  ('paper-mapreduce-google', 'Reproduce MapReduce — Simplified Data Processing', 'Dean & Ghemawat’s 2004 OSDI paper that made batch data processing trivial by exposing just two functions — map and reduce — and handling the scheduling, fault tolerance, and locality underneath. Reproducing MapReduce teaches the master/worker pattern, task re-execution on failure, and stragglers — the trio that underpins every modern data system.', 'Pick Go or Python. Build a coordinator process that hands out map and reduce tasks over RPC and a worker process that polls for work. Implement intermediate-file partitioning (hash-mod-R), local-disk persistence between map and reduce, and most importantly — task re-execution if a worker times out. Test on the canonical word-count problem against a corpus of a few hundred MB.

Compute budget — local. Run coordinator + 4 workers on your laptop. The 6.824 lab 1 is exactly this assignment and includes test scripts.

Deliverables — pass the 6.824 lab 1 test suite including the crash-recovery test where workers die mid-task. Then write up the three real-world properties you observed — speculative execution helps stragglers, partition skew hurts more than worker count helps, and intermediate-file size is the primary tuning knob. Those are the same lessons every Spark/Flink/Dataflow engineer learns the hard way.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'Google', 'OpenSource', 'OSDI 2004', 'https://research.google/pubs/mapreduce-simplified-data-processing-on-large-clusters/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"usenix.org","url":"https://www.usenix.org/legacy/event/osdi04/tech/full_papers/dean/dean.pdf"},{"label":"pdos.csail.mit.edu","url":"https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.824/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','distributed','mapreduce','big-data']::text[]),
  ('paper-gfs-google-file-system', 'Reproduce GFS — The Google File System', 'Ghemawat, Gobioff & Leung’s 2003 SOSP paper that introduced a single-master, chunk-server file system optimised for huge files, append-heavy workloads, and commodity-hardware failures. Reproducing a mini-GFS teaches replication, leases, consistency under concurrent appends, and why HDFS exists.', 'Three processes — master, chunkservers, client library. Files are split into 64MB chunks (use 4MB locally for testing); each chunk is replicated to 3 chunkservers. The master stores metadata in memory and journals changes. Implement the lease-based primary-replica protocol for writes — the primary serialises mutations and forwards them to secondaries.

Compute budget — local. Run master + 3 chunkservers + clients on one machine, or split across a couple of cheap VMs. The interesting failures (master crash, secondary lag, lease expiration during write) are easy to inject.

Deliverables — a working mini-GFS that survives chunkserver kill -9 mid-write, supports atomic record appends, and reports the master’s memory usage as a function of file count (this is the famous scalability cliff). The realisation that one master can manage petabytes because it only knows about chunks not files is the whole architectural lesson.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Google', 'OpenSource', 'SOSP 2003', 'https://research.google.com/archive/gfs-sosp2003.pdf', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"hadoop.apache.org","url":"https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/r1.2.1/hdfs_design.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','distributed','storage','gfs']::text[]),
  ('paper-dynamo-amazon', 'Reproduce Dynamo — Highly Available Key-Value Store', 'DeCandia et al.’s 2007 SOSP paper that traded strong consistency for guaranteed availability via consistent hashing, vector clocks, sloppy quorums, and hinted handoff. Reproducing Dynamo teaches the entire NoSQL playbook — Cassandra, Riak, and DynamoDB all descend from this paper.', 'Build the ring first — consistent hashing with virtual nodes, where each key maps to N successor nodes on the ring. Implement Get/Put with R + W > N tunable quorums. Tag values with vector clocks; on read, return all conflicting versions and let the client resolve. Add hinted handoff so writes during a node-failure window get replayed when the node returns.

Compute budget — local. Run a 5-node ring on one machine, inject node failures and partitions, observe what happens to availability and consistency. Use Jepsen-style consistency checks to verify your safety claims.

Deliverables — graphs of availability and latency under node-loss scenarios, plus a clear demo of a conflict — partition the ring, write different values on both sides, heal, and show vector-clock-driven divergence and reconciliation. That divergence-and-merge demo is the single best way to internalise eventual consistency.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Amazon', 'OpenSource', 'SOSP 2007', 'https://www.allthingsdistributed.com/files/amazon-dynamo-sosp2007.pdf', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"amazon.science","url":"https://www.amazon.science/publications/dynamo-amazons-highly-available-key-value-store"},{"label":"dl.acm.org","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/1294261.1294281"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','distributed','nosql','dynamo']::text[]),
  ('fossee-openfoam-cfd', 'OpenFOAM CFD Solver & Blender GUI Add-on', 'Contribute to FOSSEE OpenFOAM by writing case files for a real CFD problem of meaningful complexity, or extend the Blender add-on that lets users author multi-block geometries graphically. The team mentors interns end-to-end on meshing, solver tuning and visualisation.', 'Set up OpenFOAM v11+ on Linux/WSL and reproduce one of the published FOSSEE tutorial cases — e.g. lid-driven cavity or pitzDaily — so you are comfortable with the dictionary file structure and paraFoam.

Next, pick a screening task from the CFD-FOSSEE page: typically you propose a CFD problem (geometry + governing equations + validation source) plus a small contribution to the Blender GUI add-on. Push your solver case to a public Git repo and submit the link with your application.

Once selected, you work remotely over a full semester with weekly mentor reviews. Deliverables are upstreamed into the FOSSEE OpenFOAM case library, so write your dictionaries and READMEs to be reusable by undergraduate labs.', 'Education', 'advanced', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://cfd.fossee.in/fellowship2025', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"fossee.in","url":"https://fossee.in/semester-internship/2026"},{"label":"cfd.fossee.in","url":"https://cfd.fossee.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['cfd','openfoam','blender','simulation','fossee','iit-bombay']::text[]),
  ('fossee-esim-kicad-plugin', 'eSim — KiCad 9 Plugin & PDK Workflow', 'Build a working KiCad 9 plugin that ships inside eSim, the FOSSEE FLOSS EDA suite used as an open alternative to OrCAD and LTspice. Plugins typically tie together schematic capture, Ngspice simulation and PCB layout — touching both CS and electronics.', 'Install eSim and KiCad 9 and walk through a published example circuit so you can navigate the schematic-to-Ngspice-to-layout flow. Read the KiCad Python plugin API and pick a real pain-point — DRC reports, BoM enrichment, footprint linting — to scope your plugin.

For the parallel PDK screening task, download an open PDK such as IHP SG13G2, point Ngspice at the model library, and run a parameter sweep over a basic CMOS device, extracting the I-V data and producing plots.

Submit a GitHub repo containing the plugin source, install instructions for eSim, and a short demo video. Selected interns work for one semester to harden the plugin into a release-ready eSim feature.', 'Education', 'advanced', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://esim.fossee.in/node/185', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"esim.fossee.in","url":"https://esim.fossee.in/"},{"label":"fossee.in","url":"https://fossee.in/semester-internship/2026"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['eda','esim','kicad','ngspice','vlsi','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-openmodelica-chemical', 'OpenModelica Chemical Engineering Unit-Op Library', 'Extend the FOSSEE OpenModelica Chemical Engineering library — a steady-state and dynamic unit-operation set benchmarked against Aspen Plus and DWSIM. Interns build new models for distillation, reactors, heat exchangers and validate against published data.', 'Install OpenModelica and DWSIM side-by-side. Reproduce one of the existing FOSSEE flowsheets — e.g. methanol synthesis loop — in both tools so you understand the equation-oriented vs sequential-modular paradigms.

Pick one missing or weakly-modelled unit operation and code it in Modelica using the existing library style. Validate by comparing steady-state outputs against DWSIM and a textbook example. Submit your .mo file plus a Jupyter or LibreOffice document showing the cross-tool comparison.

During the semester you contribute multiple unit-ops, write tutorial documentation, and your work is published on the FOSSEE OpenModelica Chemical Engineering page for nationwide reuse.', 'Education', 'advanced', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://om.fossee.in/chemical', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"om.fossee.in","url":"https://om.fossee.in/resources"},{"label":"dwsim.fossee.in","url":"https://dwsim.fossee.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['modelica','chemical-engineering','process-simulation','fossee','openmodelica']::text[]),
  ('fossee-dwsim-flowsheeting', 'DWSIM Collaborative Flowsheeting Project', 'Contribute steady-state chemical process flowsheets to FOSSEE DWSIM — a fully open alternative to Aspen Plus. Over 100 validated flowsheets are already published; your job is to add new ones tied to standard textbooks and verify against literature data.', 'Install DWSIM, then complete the official FOSSEE DWSIM walkthrough on a simple two-component flash. Pick a textbook problem — Sinnott, Felder, Perry — that is not already in the FOSSEE catalogue and rebuild it in DWSIM.

For your screening task submit the .dwxmz file, a written validation showing your stream tables match the textbook within tolerance, and a PDF explaining each unit choice. The bar is engineering correctness, not GUI polish.

During the semester you typically deliver 8-10 published flowsheets, each peer-reviewed by the FOSSEE chemical team and hosted on the DWSIM project page for use by colleges across India.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://dwsim.fossee.in/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"fossee.in","url":"https://fossee.in/semester-internship/2026"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['dwsim','process-simulation','chemical-engineering','fossee','flowsheet']::text[]),
  ('fossee-osdag-lcc-web', 'Osdag LCC-Web — Laterally Restrained Beam Module', 'Osdag-on-web is the cross-platform browser version of the Osdag steel-design suite that follows IS 800:2007. Interns build new design modules — Laterally Restrained Beams, Compression Members, Bolted Splices — wiring Python design logic into the React UI.', 'Install desktop Osdag and design a sample fin-plate connection so you understand the IS 800 design flow. Then clone the Osdag-web repo and run it locally to see how design modules are registered against the React front-end.

For the screening task, pick one module — typically Compression Member or Laterally Restrained Beam — and submit a hand-calculation PDF plus a working Python script that mirrors Osdag''s CAD output. The reviewers check both your structural engineering and your code quality.

In-semester work involves adding the design module end-to-end: Python code, OCC-based 3D model, unit tests against worked examples, and a contribution to the user manual. Civil-engineering students may convert this into their BTP.', 'Education', 'advanced', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://osdag.fossee.in/join-us', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"osdag.fossee.in","url":"https://osdag.fossee.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['osdag','structural','is-800','steel-design','civil-engineering','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-r-textbook-companion', 'R Textbook Companion — Statistics & Econometrics', 'Code the solved examples of a standard statistics, econometrics or biostatistics textbook in R as a Jupyter notebook companion. FOSSEE publishes the companions for free use by colleges and pays an honorarium of Rs. 10,000 per completed book.', 'Pick a textbook from the FOSSEE R Textbook Companion proposal list — only books not already claimed are eligible. Submit a proposal form listing chapter coverage and at least 60 candidate solved examples.

On approval, install R + IRkernel and set up a Jupyter notebook per chapter. Convert each solved example into runnable R code, validate that the output matches the printed textbook value, and document inputs/outputs in Markdown above each cell.

Submissions are peer-reviewed by the FOSSEE R team; revisions are usually requested. Once accepted, your name and book are hosted on the R Textbook Companion site as a permanent academic credit.', 'Education', 'beginner', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Textbook Companion', 'https://r.fossee.org/textbook-companion/textbook-companion-internship', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"fossee.in","url":"https://fossee.in/fossee-internships"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['r','statistics','textbook-companion','jupyter','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-python-tbc-engineering', 'Python Textbook Companion for Engineering', 'Convert the solved examples of a standard engineering textbook into a Python Jupyter notebook companion that joins the 500+ already published by FOSSEE. Books span thermodynamics, electrical machines, signals & systems, control theory and more.', 'Browse the existing Python Textbook Companion catalogue at tbc-python.fossee.in to confirm your target textbook is unclaimed. Submit the formal proposal with a chapter-wise plan and the estimated solved-example count.

For each chapter create a Jupyter notebook reproducing every solved example as runnable Python. Use NumPy/SciPy/Matplotlib for numeric and plotting needs and keep every variable name as in the textbook to ease grading.

Once all chapters pass FOSSEE review, the honorarium of Rs. 10,000 is released and your notebooks are hosted on the FOSSEE GitHub mirror and the public TBC portal.', 'Education', 'beginner', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Python Textbook Companion', 'https://tbc-python.fossee.in/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/FOSSEE/Python-Textbook-Companions"},{"label":"python.fossee.in","url":"https://python.fossee.in/textbook-companion-project/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['python','jupyter','textbook-companion','engineering-education','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-ngi-geospatial', 'National Geospatial Internship — District-Level QGIS Mapping', 'FOSSEE GIS in partnership with RuDRA, IIT Bombay runs the National Geospatial Internship — 1,000 students, one per district, each producing an open-source QGIS dashboard on a focus theme such as agriculture, hydrology, climate or rural development.', 'Install QGIS LTR and complete the FOSSEE Spoken Tutorial series on QGIS basics. Pick a district plus a focused theme — for example, groundwater recharge in Pune or paddy yield in Thanjavur.

Apply via the NGI 2025 portal selecting your district and theme. Once allotted, source open data from Bhuvan, data.gov.in and ISRO Geo-platform, build the analytical layers, and finally publish a QGIS-server or Lizmap dashboard.

The six-month pro-bono internship culminates in a peer-reviewed map + a short report, hosted on the FOSSEE GIS portal as a public-good geospatial asset for your district.', 'Govt', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE GIS, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'National Geospatial Internship 2025', 'https://fossee.in/NGI2025', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"gis.fossee.in","url":"https://gis.fossee.in/gis-internship"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['qgis','gis','geospatial','rural-development','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-focal-animation-library', 'FOCAL — Open-Source Science & Math Animations', 'FOCAL is the FOSSEE creative-arts library. Fellows produce 1-2 minute Manim, Blender, VPython or Synfig animations explaining a math or science concept, then upload them to the FOSSEE animations repository for nationwide classroom use.', 'Pick a concept that is poorly served by existing material on animations.fossee.in — e.g. eigenvector geometry, Bernoulli flow, or HCl hybridisation. Storyboard it on paper before touching software.

For the screening task, build one 30-60 second clip in Manim or Blender and submit the source plus rendered MP4. Reviewers look for didactic clarity over flashy visuals.

During the fellowship you deliver 4-6 finished animations, each accompanied by an annotated source repo so other teachers can fork and remix. All assets are CC-BY-SA and live on the FOSSEE animations portal.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE FOCAL, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Summer Fellowship 2026', 'https://focal.fossee.in/node/375', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"animations.fossee.in","url":"https://animations.fossee.in/"},{"label":"focal.fossee.in","url":"https://focal.fossee.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['manim','blender','animation','science-education','fossee','focal']::text[]),
  ('fossee-scilab-toolbox-signal', 'Scilab Toolbox — Signal & Image Processing', 'Extend the FOSSEE Scilab toolboxes — Signal Processing, Image Processing, Control Systems, Optimisation or Scilab-to-C. Interns implement missing functions that match the equivalent MATLAB API so faculty can migrate course material to a fully FOSS stack.', 'Install Scilab plus the relevant toolbox and reproduce a published demo to learn the macro vs gateway split. Identify a missing function — say medfilt2 or cheby1 — by diffing against MATLAB documentation.

For the screening task implement that function as a .sci macro, write a Scilab unit test that compares its output against a reference vector, and submit a tarball with a README.

The semester deliverable is a fully documented set of new toolbox functions, demos and Spoken-Tutorial slides ready for publication on scilab.in.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE Scilab, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Scilab Toolbox Fellowship', 'https://scilab.in/fellowship2018/scilab-toolbox', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"scilab.in","url":"https://scilab.in/esim"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['scilab','signal-processing','image-processing','toolbox','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-aai-mapathon', 'IITB-FOSSEE AAI Airports Mapathon', 'Join the FOSSEE x Airports Authority of India Mapathon — students crowdsource detailed open-data maps of Indian airports and their surrounding infrastructure in QGIS, feeding directly into AAI planning workflows.', 'Register on the IITB-FOSSEE AAI Mapathon 2025 portal and pick an airport tile. Complete the bundled QGIS training that introduces OSM data, Bhuvan imagery and the AAI digitising standard.

Digitise the assigned runway, taxiway, terminal and access infrastructure as GeoJSON layers. Submit them via the mapathon portal where the FOSSEE GIS team validates topology and attribute completeness.

Validated contributors get an IIT Bombay e-certificate and rank on the public leaderboard. Top maps may be cited by AAI and FOSSEE in joint reports.', 'Govt', 'beginner', 'FOSSEE GIS, IIT Bombay x AAI', 'OpenSource', 'IITB-FOSSEE AAI Mapathon 2025', 'https://iitb-aai-mapathon-2025.fossee.in/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"iitb-fossee-mapathon.fossee.in","url":"https://iitb-fossee-mapathon.fossee.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['mapathon','qgis','airports','aai','fossee','crowdsourcing']::text[]),
  ('fossee-drupal-modules', 'Drupal — Custom Module Migration & Maintenance', 'Maintain and forward-port FOSSEE''s family of Drupal sites — Spoken Tutorial, Textbook Companion, Lab Migration. The internship focuses on writing custom modules and migrating legacy Drupal 7 code to Drupal 10.', 'Set up a Drupal 10 local stack with DDEV. Read the FOSSEE migration brief which lists the candidate modules and the legacy schema. Pick one small module — a workshop registration form, a CSV-export, or a custom dashboard block.

For the screening task you fix one reproducible bug or implement one minor enhancement and submit the patch as a Git PR against a sandbox repository.

In-semester deliverables: at least one fully migrated module published on drupal.org or the FOSSEE GitHub, including upgrade docs and rollback notes.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://fossee.in/semester-internship/2026', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"fossee.in","url":"https://fossee.in/fossee-internships"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['drupal','php','cms','migration','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-django-react-internship', 'Hybrid Django + React Tools for FOSSEE Portals', 'Build hybrid web-desktop tools that power FOSSEE workflows — Textbook Companion submission portals, eSim cloud dashboards, lab-migration trackers. Stack is Django REST + React with PyQt5 wrappers for offline use.', 'Read the screening brief on fossee.in/semester-internship/2026 — recent rounds require a full-stack chemical-data visualisation portal with Django REST API, React dashboard and a PyQt5 desktop client. A reference submission lives at github.com/Mayukh-Jain/FOSSEE_Internship_2026.

Clone the brief''s starter dataset, design the API contract, and submit a working repo plus a short Loom-style walkthrough.

Semester work hardens the prototype into a deployed portal — Postgres + Docker compose, RBAC, audit logs — for use by FOSSEE staff across projects.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'FOSSEE, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', 'FOSSEE Semester Long Internship 2026', 'https://fossee.in/semester-internship/2026', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/Mayukh-Jain/FOSSEE_Internship_2026"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['django','react','pyqt5','full-stack','fossee']::text[]),
  ('fossee-spoken-tutorial-content', 'Spoken Tutorial — Create FOSS Course Content', 'Spoken Tutorial is FOSSEE''s video-based learning platform with millions of certified learners. Contributors write scripts, record screencasts and produce subtitles for Python, R, LaTeX, LibreOffice, Linux and more — in multiple Indian languages.', 'Pick a FOSS tool from the Spoken Tutorial gap list — e.g. an advanced Python topic, a new LibreOffice Impress workflow, or a regional-language port of an existing English tutorial.

Download the official script template, write a 7-10 minute script following the house style, and record using SimpleScreenRecorder or Kazam. Submit script + recording for domain review.

Once approved, your video joins the Spoken Tutorial catalogue and is freely available under CC-BY-SA, often used in MeitY-sponsored training across Indian colleges.', 'Education', 'beginner', 'Spoken Tutorial, IIT Bombay', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://spoken-tutorial.org/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"python.fossee.in","url":"https://python.fossee.in/spoken-tutorials/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['spoken-tutorial','video','foss-education','indian-languages','fossee']::text[]),
  ('foss-united-fosshack', 'FOSS Hack — Weekend Build for a New FOSS Project', 'FOSS Hack is FOSS United''s flagship hackathon — 1600+ teams build new open-source projects in 48 hours. Past winners include farm-advisory NLP tools, caregiver tracking apps and self-hostable feedback widgets, all GPL/MIT licensed.', 'Form a team of 1-4 and register on fossunited.org/fosshack. Read the rules — projects must be born during the hackathon and licensed under an OSI-approved licence.

Before the weekend, scope a sharp problem statement: an Indic-language tool, a civic dashboard, a developer utility. Sketch architecture and define a minimum demo that judges can run locally in under five minutes.

During the hack, push commits often, write a clear README, and submit via the FOSS United portal. Winning teams get cash prizes; many projects go on to receive follow-on FOSS United grants.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'FOSS United Foundation', 'OpenSource', 'FOSS Hack 2025', 'https://fossunited.org/fosshack/2025', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"fossunited.org","url":"https://fossunited.org/hack/fosshack24"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['hackathon','foss-united','open-source','weekend-build']::text[]),
  ('foss-united-clubs', 'FOSS Clubs — Campus FOSS Project Pipeline', 'FOSS United Clubs are college chapters where students run study circles, build FOSS for their campus, and contribute upstream. The foundation funds promising club projects through micro-grants and mentors them to release readiness.', 'Form a 5+ member team at your college and register a FOSS Club on fossunited.org/clubs. Once recognised, choose a campus pain-point — attendance, hostel mess feedback, a course-resource portal — to FOSS-ify.

Apply for the FOSS United project grant with a one-pager covering problem, scope, licence (MIT/AGPL), milestones and budget. Approved teams get monthly mentor calls and INR funding tied to milestones.

Deliver a 1.0 release on GitHub with CI, docs and a 5-minute demo video. Showcase the project at IndiaFOSS and at the FOSS United city-community meet nearest you.', 'OpenSource', 'beginner', 'FOSS United Foundation', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://fossunited.org/clubs', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/fossunited"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['foss-clubs','student-community','foss-united','grants']::text[]),
  ('foss-united-indiafoss-talk', 'IndiaFOSS — Propose a Talk or Workshop', 'IndiaFOSS is FOSS United''s annual conference — 2026 edition runs 26-27 September in Bengaluru. Students who maintain or contribute meaningfully to a FOSS project can submit a talk, lightning or workshop CFP and get reimbursed travel.', 'Pick a FOSS project you genuinely contributed to — bug fixes shipped, modules upstreamed, or a working prototype. Draft a 200-word abstract that maps to one of the IndiaFOSS tracks: developer tools, AI/ML, Indic, civic-tech, hardware.

Submit via the CFP portal at fossunited.org/indiafoss. Selected speakers get travel reimbursed plus access to the maintainers'' day.

Use the talk as a forcing function to finish your project — record a screencast demo, write a launch blog, and publish v1.0 on GitHub before the conference.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'FOSS United Foundation', 'OpenSource', 'IndiaFOSS 2025', 'https://fossunited.org/indiafoss/2025', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"indiafoss.net","url":"https://indiafoss.net/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['indiafoss','conference','cfp','foss-united','speaker']::text[]),
  ('openforge-digilocker-contrib', 'OpenForge — DigiLocker Module Contribution', 'OpenForge is the Govt of India''s GitHub-equivalent for e-Governance code. DigiLocker hosts identity, certificate and KYC integrations used by 200M+ Indians; the project takes external code, UX-audit, security-test and docs contributions.', 'Create a free OpenForge account and read the DigiLocker project listing at openforge.gov.in/openforge/digilocker.php. The platform runs on Tuleap; explore the issue tracker and pick a small UX-audit, accessibility, or doc gap to start with.

For security testing, run OWASP ZAP / Nikto against the public sandbox endpoints and submit a responsible-disclosure report through the listed channel. Avoid touching production endpoints.

Larger code contributions usually require an MoU; engage NeGD/MeitY via the openforge.gov.in/credits.php contacts before submitting patches. Accepted PRs become part of India''s digital public infrastructure.', 'Govt', 'intermediate', 'NeGD, MeitY', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://openforge.gov.in/openforge/digilocker.php', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"openforge.gov.in","url":"https://openforge.gov.in/"},{"label":"negd.gov.in","url":"https://negd.gov.in/openforge/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['digilocker','openforge','e-governance','meity','digital-india']::text[]),
  ('openforge-umang-app', 'OpenForge — UMANG App Service Plugin', 'UMANG is the unified mobile platform exposing 1000+ central and state e-Gov services. OpenForge hosts the integration kit so partner developers can build new service plugins — utility bill payments, scholarship portals, departmental lookups.', 'Register on OpenForge and join the UMANG project space. Read the partner-developer SDK docs to understand the service-onboarding contract — REST schema, OTP-based auth and the localisation requirement (13+ Indian languages).

For your screening contribution, pick a small state-level service that is missing on UMANG and prototype its plugin against the sandbox APIs. Document the user journey, accessibility considerations and language coverage.

File your design under OpenForge''s UMANG tracker; the project team will guide you through MeitY-empanelment formalities if your prototype gets shortlisted.', 'Govt', 'advanced', 'NeGD, MeitY', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://openforge.gov.in/openforge/umang.php', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"openforge.gov.in","url":"https://openforge.gov.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['umang','openforge','mobile','e-governance','meity']::text[]),
  ('openforge-gem-marketplace', 'OpenForge — GeM Marketplace Tooling', 'Government e-Marketplace (GeM) is India''s largest public-procurement platform — INR 4 lakh-crore+ transacted annually. Its OpenForge project takes contributions in catalog tooling, vendor onboarding scripts, analytics and reporting plugins.', 'Sign up on OpenForge and request access to the GeM project workspace. Pick a contained area — say, a Python script that audits seller catalogs for HSN-code mismatches, or a Metabase dashboard against the published GeM transaction dataset.

Produce a working prototype using data from data.gov.in (GeM open datasets are listed there). Document install, run and verification steps in the project README.

Upload the patch via OpenForge''s Tuleap repo and tag the GeM coordinators for review. Accepted tooling can be deployed inside the production GeM environment by NeGD.', 'Govt', 'advanced', 'NeGD, MeitY', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://openforge.gov.in/openforge/gem.php', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"openforge.gov.in","url":"https://openforge.gov.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['gem','procurement','openforge','e-governance','data-analytics']::text[]),
  ('openforge-poshan-tracker', 'OpenForge — Poshan Tracker Analytics Module', 'Poshan Tracker is the MoWCD nutrition-monitoring platform tracking 10 crore beneficiaries through 14 lakh Anganwadi Centres. Contributors can build offline-first survey modules, multilingual UI fixes or analytics dashboards on de-identified data.', 'Access the Poshan Tracker project on OpenForge and read the documented data dictionary — height, weight, MUAC, growth-chart fields. The sandbox is sanitised; respect the data-protection policy.

Pick a contained module — an offline-first React Native form for Anganwadi workers, or a Python script that flags growth-faltering trajectories. Build against the sandbox APIs.

Submit the patch via the OpenForge tracker. Strong contributions often progress to a MoWCD partnership for field piloting in one ICDS block.', 'Health', 'intermediate', 'MoWCD, Govt of India', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://openforge.gov.in/openforge/poshan.php', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"openforge.gov.in","url":"https://openforge.gov.in/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['poshan','nutrition','anganwadi','openforge','health','mowcd']::text[]),
  ('isro-api-spacecraft', 'ISRO Open Spacecraft & Launch Vehicle API', 'ISRO maintains a single official GitHub repo — isro/api — a Jupyter-based open API exposing data on every spacecraft and launch vehicle India has flown. Contributions cover new endpoints, payload metadata, mission timelines and client SDKs.', 'Fork github.com/isro/api and run the Jupyter notebooks locally to understand the data shape. Each mission record is a JSON entry; gaps include payload mass details, telemetry frequencies and post-mission status updates.

For a first PR, add or correct one mission record using ISRO''s public press releases as the citation. Keep the schema consistent and update the README example queries if your field is new.

Larger contributions — say, a Python client library, a Postman collection, or a static documentation site — should be opened as an issue first to align on scope with the maintainers.', 'OpenSource', 'beginner', 'ISRO', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://github.com/isro/api', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/isro"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['isro','space','api','jupyter','open-data']::text[]),
  ('isro-bhuvan-geo-apps', 'ISRO Bhuvan — Geospatial App Crowdsourcing', 'Bhuvan is NRSC/ISRO''s geo-platform built on open-source GeoServer, MapServer, OpenLayers and PHP. Students develop geospatial applications using Bhuvan APIs and contribute crowdsourced data on land use, water bodies and infrastructure.', 'Create a free Bhuvan developer account and complete the ISRO three-day app-development webinar (offered annually to UG/PG students). The webinar walks through Bhuvan WMS/WFS endpoints and the OpenLayers integration pattern.

Pick a use-case — flood inundation mapper, district crop calendar, urban-heat-island viewer — and build a single-page app that consumes Bhuvan tiles plus a state OGD dataset.

Submit the app and any new crowdsourced point/polygon data via the Bhuvan contribute portal; after authentication by ISRO, accepted layers are published nationally.', 'Govt', 'intermediate', 'NRSC, ISRO', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://bhuvan.nrsc.gov.in/ngmaps', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"bhuvan-app1.nrsc.gov.in","url":"https://bhuvan-app1.nrsc.gov.in/bhuvantraining/index.php"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['isro','bhuvan','geospatial','geoserver','openlayers','remote-sensing']::text[]),
  ('sunbird-diksha-microservices', 'Sunbird / DIKSHA — Microservice & Plugin Contribution', 'DIKSHA, India''s national school-education platform, runs on Sunbird — 100+ MIT-licensed microservices serving content in 36 Indian languages. The Sunbird community welcomes contributions to content players, analytics, mobile and language modules.', 'Browse the Sunbird GitHub org and pick a beginner-friendly issue tagged good-first-issue. Set up the local dev stack using the Sunbird-ED Helm charts on a Kubernetes cluster (minikube works for most services).

Common entry points are the Mobile App (React Native), the Content Player (Angular), or the Analytics Pipeline (Scala/Druid). Pick the surface that matches your strongest stack.

Submit PRs against the relevant Sunbird repo; the Sunbird Architecture Working Group reviews weekly. Accepted PRs ship to DIKSHA, reaching tens of millions of learners.', 'Education', 'advanced', 'NCERT / Sunbird', 'OpenSource', NULL, 'https://diksha.gov.in/help/diksha-oss/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/Sunbird-Obsrv/Community"},{"label":"sunbird.org","url":"https://sunbird.org/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['sunbird','diksha','edtech','microservices','ncert','indic']::text[]),
  ('bhashini-indic-language-models', 'Bhashini — Indic Language Model & Tooling Contribution', 'Bhashini is the National Language Translation Mission — open ASR, MT and TTS models for 22 Indian languages released as digital public goods. Students contribute datasets, fine-tunes, evaluation harnesses and downstream apps via Bhashini hackathons.', 'Register on bhashini.gov.in and pick a language pair or task — Mizo ASR, Marathi-to-Hindi MT, Tamil TTS. Pull the corresponding model from the Bhashini model catalogue and run a baseline benchmark on a public test set.

For a screening contribution, build either a finetune that improves WER/BLEU on the chosen benchmark, or a downstream app — a Whisper-style transcription web tool, a judicial-document translator for the Bhasha Bandhu track, or a public-services chatbot.

Submit your work through the relevant Bhashini hackathon (Bhasha Bandhu, Startup Velocity, Domain Innovation Challenge). Top submissions receive funding plus pilot access to government deployments.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Bhashini, MeitY', 'OpenSource', 'Bhasha Bandhu Hackathon 2025', 'https://bhashini.gov.in/hackathon', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"innovateindia.mygov.in","url":"https://innovateindia.mygov.in/bhashini-challenge/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['bhashini','nlp','indic','asr','translation','meity']::text[]),
  ('uni-mit-6828-xv6-os', 'MIT 6.1810/6.S081 — xv6 RISC-V kernel labs', 'Modify the xv6 teaching kernel (a Unix V6 reimplementation in C, running on QEMU RISC-V) by adding real OS features — system calls, page tables, trap handlers, copy-on-write fork, an mmap implementation, and a thread-safe file system. Ten labs take you from printing a hello kernel message to debugging racy locks under the kernel scheduler.', 'Clone the official xv6-riscv repo from the 6.S081 site, install the RISC-V GNU toolchain and QEMU, and run make qemu — you boot into the xv6 shell inside seconds. Read the xv6 book (PDF on the course site) cover-to-cover for the first three chapters before touching code; it explains how trap.c, proc.c, and vm.c fit together.

Start with Lab Util (write a sleep userland program and a pingpong IPC test) to learn the build system, then move to Lab Syscall where you add a trace syscall. The page-tables lab is the first big jump — you implement a per-process page table that maps user memory into the kernel for fast copy_in/copy_out. By the time you reach the mmap lab you are reading dirty bits and lazy-allocating frame mappings.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'MIT', 'OpenSource', 'MIT 6.1810 Fall 2024', 'https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.828/2024/xv6.html', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"pdos.csail.mit.edu","url":"https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.828/2024/xv6/book-riscv-rev3.pdf"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/mit-pdos/xv6-riscv"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['operating-systems','systems','kernel','c','risc-v']::text[]),
  ('uni-mit-6824-distributed', 'MIT 6.5840 — Raft, MapReduce and sharded KV in Go', 'Build a fault-tolerant distributed key-value store from scratch in Go. Across five labs you implement MapReduce, a basic key-value server, the Raft consensus protocol (leader election, log replication, snapshotting), a Raft-backed KV service, and finally a sharded KV with reconfiguration.', 'Grab the lab skeleton from the 6.5840 git repo — it ships RPC primitives, a deterministic network simulator, and a test harness that injects partitions, crashes, and reordered messages. Read the Raft paper (Ongaro and Ousterhout 2014) twice before writing a line of code. The provided labrpc package fakes the network; failing tests will print sequences of partition events so you can replay them.

Lab 1 (MapReduce) is mostly a warm-up — write a worker that pulls tasks from a coordinator over RPC. Lab 3 (Raft) is where most students spend three weeks: implement RequestVote and AppendEntries, then layer on persistence and log compaction. Each test runs the tester many times under different schedules — if you have a 1-in-50 race, the harness will find it.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'MIT', 'OpenSource', 'MIT 6.5840 Spring 2026', 'https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.824/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"raft.github.io","url":"https://raft.github.io/raft.pdf"},{"label":"pdos.csail.mit.edu","url":"https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.824/papers/mapreduce.pdf"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['distributed-systems','raft','go','consensus','fault-tolerance']::text[]),
  ('uni-cmu-15445-bustub', 'CMU 15-445 — BusTub disk-oriented database', 'Implement the guts of a real relational DBMS — buffer pool manager with LRU-K replacement, an extendible hash index, the iterator-model query executor (filter, join, aggregate), and concurrency control with two-phase locking. The skeleton is BusTub, a production-grade educational engine on GitHub.', 'Fork the bustub repo (cmu-db/bustub on GitHub) and build it with the provided CMake config — it runs on Linux and macOS with clang. Project 0 is a C++ primer (a trie data structure) used to weed out students who cannot handle the codebase. Projects 1-4 each have hidden Gradescope tests and a public local test suite — make check-clang-tidy and make submit-pX are your friends.

For Project 1 (Buffer Pool Manager) start with the LRU-K replacer, then the disk scheduler, then the manager itself — each piece has a clean interface in include/buffer/. Project 2 (Hash Index) wants you to implement extendible hashing on top of buffer-pool-backed pages, which means you debug page latches as much as the hash logic itself. Project 4 (Concurrency Control) finally turns BusTub into a multi-user database by adding lock manager, deadlock detection, and MVCC.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Carnegie Mellon University', 'OpenSource', 'CMU 15-445 Fall 2023', 'https://15445.courses.cs.cmu.edu/fall2023/assignments.html', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/cmu-db/bustub"},{"label":"15445.courses.cs.cmu.edu","url":"https://15445.courses.cs.cmu.edu/fall2023/notes/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['databases','systems','cpp','concurrency','indexing']::text[]),
  ('uni-cmu-15213-malloclab', 'CMU 15-213 — bomb lab, attack lab, malloc lab, proxy lab', 'The legendary CS:APP lab suite. Defuse a binary bomb by reverse-engineering x86-64 assembly, exploit a vulnerable C program via return-oriented programming, write your own segregated-free-list malloc, and build a caching HTTP proxy that handles concurrent clients.', 'The labs are distributed as tarballs from the course Autolab — each contains a Makefile, starter sources, and an opaque handout binary. For Bomb Lab you only get the ELF; fire it up in gdb, disassemble each phase_N function, and figure out the input string that avoids explode_bomb. Set breakpoints on strings_not_equal and read the register state.

Malloc Lab is the rite of passage — start by implementing an implicit free list with first-fit (you get ~50% utilization), then upgrade to segregated lists with mini-blocks for the leaderboard score. The provided tracefile-driven simulator scores throughput and utilization. Proxy Lab finally puts pthreads, robust I/O, and a small LRU web cache together into a working HTTP/1.0 proxy you can run in your browser.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Carnegie Mellon University', 'OpenSource', 'CMU 15-213 Spring 2024', 'https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~213/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"csapp.cs.cmu.edu","url":"http://csapp.cs.cmu.edu/3e/labs.html"},{"label":"cs.cmu.edu","url":"https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~213/labs.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','c','assembly','security','memory']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs231n', 'Stanford CS231n — CNNs for visual recognition from scratch', 'Write the forward and backward passes of fully-connected nets, convolutional layers, batch norm, dropout, RNNs, and finally a small Transformer — all in NumPy first, then PyTorch. Train on CIFAR-10 and image-captioning datasets, then finish with a multi-million-parameter group project on a real vision task.', 'Assignments are distributed as Jupyter notebooks via the course site — each one has TODO blocks and a unit-test grader that compares your gradient against a finite-difference oracle. Assignment 1 (kNN, SVM, softmax, two-layer net) forces you to vectorize NumPy code — students who skip this struggle with the conv backward pass later.

Assignment 2 implements convolution and batch norm by hand; the trick is the im2col reshape that turns conv into a single matmul. Assignment 3 covers RNN captioning, self-attention, and finally the Transformer block. The final project (35% of grade) is open — train and apply a multi-million parameter network to a vision problem of your choice with cloud credits from Modal, AWS, and GCP.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS231n Spring 2025', 'https://cs231n.stanford.edu/', '[{"label":"CIFAR-10","url":"https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html","format":"images"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"cs231n.github.io","url":"https://cs231n.github.io/"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/cs231n/cs231n.github.io"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ml','computer-vision','deep-learning','python','pytorch']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs224n-mingpt', 'Stanford CS224n — minimalist GPT-2 from scratch', 'Build word vectors, a neural dependency parser, a self-attention block, and finally a working GPT-2 reimplementation in PyTorch that you fine-tune on three downstream NLP tasks. The default final project (minBERT/minGPT) is the canonical from-scratch transformer codebase students fork all over GitHub.', 'Assignments are released as PyTorch notebook + .py skeletons via Gradescope. Assignment 1 walks you through co-occurrence-matrix word vectors and word2vec analogies on the Reuters corpus. Assignment 2 has you derive tensor gradients by hand, then implement a transition-based dependency parser.

Assignment 3 implements scaled dot-product attention, multi-head attention, and positional encodings from scratch. The default final project ships a starter repo containing a GPT-2 architecture with several missing pieces — you complete the LayerNorm, attention, and AdamW optimizer, then fine-tune on paraphrase detection, sentiment, and sonnet generation. Compute credits come from Google, Kimi, Modal, and Qwen.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS224n Winter 2026', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs224n/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/karpathy/minGPT"},{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs224n/index.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ml','nlp','transformers','pytorch','deep-learning']::text[]),
  ('uni-berkeley-cs162-pintos', 'Berkeley CS162 — Pintos OS (user programs, threads, file system)', 'Extend the Pintos kernel — a 80x86 teaching OS — by implementing argument passing and the system call interface for user programs, then priority-donating thread synchronization, and finally a fully buffered, journalled file system with subdirectories. Each project is a guided redesign of a major OS subsystem.', 'Clone the Pintos starter from the CS162 staff repo and bring up the bochs/qemu emulator with make check. Project 0 (Pregame) is a four-question warm-up that makes sure your toolchain works.

Project 1 (User Programs) starts in userprog/process.c — you wire up argument passing on the user stack, then implement halt/exit/exec/wait/file syscalls. Project 2 (Threads) is the algorithm-heavy one: priority scheduling with donation across nested locks, plus the multi-level feedback queue scheduler. Project 3 (File System) replaces the flat indexed allocation with an inode-based tree, adds a buffer cache with LRU eviction, and supports chdir/mkdir.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'UC Berkeley', 'OpenSource', 'Berkeley CS162 Spring 2024', 'https://cs162.org/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs140/projects/pintos/pintos.html"},{"label":"cs162.org","url":"https://cs162.org/static/proj/pintos-docs/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['operating-systems','systems','c','kernel','synchronization']::text[]),
  ('uni-berkeley-cs186-rookiedb', 'Berkeley CS186 — RookieDB: B+ trees, joins, locking, recovery', 'Add seven major subsystems to RookieDB, a Java teaching database — disk-backed B+ tree indexes, sort/hash/grace-hash join operators, the Selinger query optimizer, hierarchical S/X/IS/IX/SIX locks, and ARIES write-ahead recovery. Finishes with a NoSQL/MongoDB-style aggregation pipeline.', 'Fork the public CS186 fa20 reference repo and import as Gradle project — the test harness uses JUnit and runs both sample and hidden tests via Gradescope. Project 0 walks you through the codebase architecture (TableIterator, Table, RecordId).

Project 2 (B+ Tree) is the first deep dive — you implement leaf and inner-node split/merge and serialize each node into a buffer-managed disk page. Project 3 (Joins + Query Optimization) builds three join algorithms then a System-R-style dynamic-programming optimizer that costs plans using histograms. Project 4 (Locking) implements the lock manager and the lock-context tree that handles intention locks. Project 5 (Recovery) writes the WAL, then replays it with the analysis-redo-undo three pass ARIES algorithm.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'UC Berkeley', 'OpenSource', 'Berkeley CS186 Spring 2024', 'https://cs186berkeley.net/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/berkeley-cs186/sp24-rookiedb"},{"label":"cs186berkeley.net","url":"https://cs186berkeley.net/resources/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['databases','java','indexing','transactions','recovery']::text[]),
  ('uni-berkeley-cs61a-scheme', 'Berkeley CS61A — Hog, Cats, Ants, Scheme interpreter', 'Build four progressively harder Python projects: a dice game with strategy analysis, a typing-test web app with autocorrect, a tower-defense game using OOP, and finally a complete Scheme interpreter in Python (lexer, parser, evaluator, tail-call optimization, macros). The Scheme project is the famous capstone every Berkeley alum remembers.', 'Course materials are open at cs61a.org — download the project zip for each, unzip into a folder, and run python3 ok to check tests. Hog teaches control flow and higher-order functions; you write play(strategy0, strategy1, ...) and then design a winning strategy against the staff bot.

Cats introduces dictionaries and iterators by computing Levenshtein distance for autocorrect on the Brown corpus. Ants is your OOP test — every ant and bee is a class with action(gamestate) polymorphism. The Scheme interpreter is implemented in Python in two halves — first scheme_eval and scheme_apply for a working evaluator, then continuations and define-macro so the interpreter can run macros from the Scheme standard library.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'UC Berkeley', 'OpenSource', 'Berkeley CS61A Spring 2026', 'https://cs61a.org/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"cs61a.org","url":"https://cs61a.org/articles/about/"},{"label":"composingprograms.com","url":"https://composingprograms.com/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['interpreters','python','scheme','ood','education']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs143-cool', 'Stanford CS143 — Cool language compiler', 'Build a complete compiler for Cool (Classroom Object-Oriented Language) across five assignments — Flex-based lexer, Bison parser building the AST, semantic analyzer with type checking and class graph validation, and a code generator that emits SPIM MIPS assembly. The output binary actually runs in the SPIM simulator.', 'Sign up for the Stanford SCPD/Lagunita mirror or pull the compilers MOOC starter from the course site — it ships a Linux VM with Flex, Bison, and the SPIM simulator preconfigured. The Cool reference manual (PDF on the course page) defines the grammar and runtime conventions precisely.

PA1 is the lexer in Flex — match keywords, integers, strings (with escape handling), and produce a stream of typed tokens. PA2 wires up Bison productions to construct AST nodes defined in cool-tree.h. PA3 does the heavy semantic work: build the inheritance graph, check no cycles, then a recursive type-check pass with subtype-aware least-upper-bound. PA4 (code generation) emits MIPS that allocates objects on a heap, dispatches via vtables, and runs garbage collection. By the end, mycoolc file.cl && spim file.s runs your compiled program.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS143 Winter 2024', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs143/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"theory.stanford.edu","url":"https://theory.stanford.edu/~aiken/software/cool/cool.html"},{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs143/handouts/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['compilers','lexer','parser','cpp','mips']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs148-raytracer', 'Stanford CS148 — physically-based ray tracer', 'Build a path-traced renderer from scratch — primary ray generation, BVH acceleration, Lambertian and microfacet BRDFs, area-light sampling, reflection and refraction with Fresnel, depth of field, and motion blur. Grading is weighted toward the visual impressiveness of the final image you render.', 'The course ships a minimal C++ starter that handles scene parsing (OBJ + JSON), a stub Renderer::trace_ray, and a PPM image writer. Start by getting a single sphere to display under a directional light — once you have that, every later feature is an additive change to the integrator.

Add the BVH using SAH partitioning so triangle meshes render in seconds, not minutes. Then split rendering into a recursive radiance(ray, depth) that does Russell-style next-event-estimation: at every shading point you sample both the BRDF and the lights, weighting with multiple importance sampling. Finish with depth-of-field (jitter the eye point on a lens disk) and motion blur (sample time across the shutter interval). Final demos are graded live for visual quality.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS148 Fall 2024', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs148/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"pbr-book.org","url":"https://www.pbr-book.org/"},{"label":"raytracing.github.io","url":"https://raytracing.github.io/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['graphics','ray-tracing','cpp','rendering']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs255-crypto', 'Stanford CS255 — password manager and end-to-end chat client', 'Implement two cryptographic systems against real-world threat models. Project 1 is a password manager with a KDF-derived master key, HMAC-tagged entries, and swap-tolerant storage. Project 2 is an end-to-end-encrypted chat client implementing the Double Ratchet (Signal-style forward secrecy and post-compromise security).', 'Both projects ship as TypeScript/JavaScript starters from the course site — they vendor in subtle-crypto and a test harness that runs adversary scenarios (key compromise, swap attacks, message reordering). Read the provided spec carefully — the threat model is the assignment, the code is just an enforcement of it.

For the password manager, derive the master key with PBKDF2, then derive per-entry HMAC keys so an adversary cannot tell whether two entries share a password. The KVS must be tamper-evident — any modification by the adversary must cause get to throw. Project 2 implements X3DH for the initial handshake, then the Double Ratchet — chain keys, root keys, header encryption — so that compromising any single message key never reveals past or future messages.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS255 Winter 2025', 'https://crypto.stanford.edu/~dabo/cs255/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"signal.org","url":"https://signal.org/docs/specifications/doubleratchet/"},{"label":"crypto.stanford.edu","url":"https://crypto.stanford.edu/~dabo/cryptobook/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['security','cryptography','typescript','signal-protocol']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs329s-mlsys', 'Stanford CS329S — production ML system end-to-end', 'Design, build, and deploy a complete machine learning application — data pipeline, feature store, model training, online serving, monitoring, and rollback. The single semester-long project (65 percent of grade) culminates in a demo day and most teams open-source the final repo.', 'There is no skeleton — every team picks a real problem (recommendation, fraud, content moderation, RAG over docs) and builds the entire stack. The course lectures map onto a reference architecture: ingestion (batch + streaming), feature engineering, model training with versioning, an inference service behind a load balancer, and dashboards for data drift and prediction skew.

Week 1 of the project is the proposal — define success metrics, data sources, and the latency budget. Weeks 2-6 build the data and training pipelines; tools commonly used include Airflow or Prefect, dbt, Feast for the feature store, and Weights and Biases or MLflow for experiment tracking. Weeks 7-10 stand up the serving layer (FastAPI or BentoML) with shadow deployment, A/B testing, and CloudWatch-style alarms on input distributions.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS329S Winter 2022', 'https://stanford-cs329s.github.io/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"huyenchip.com","url":"https://huyenchip.com/ml-interviews-book/"},{"label":"stanford-cs329s.github.io","url":"https://stanford-cs329s.github.io/syllabus.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ml','mlops','systems','production','deployment']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs168-toolbox', 'Stanford CS168 — modern algorithmic toolbox mini-projects', 'Nine weekly mini-projects, each combining theory with implementation — locality-sensitive hashing for similarity search, PCA and SVD on real datasets, spectral clustering on graphs, word embeddings with analogy evaluation, FFT-based audio classification, and a differential-privacy data release. Each project takes a different real dataset.', 'Starter notebooks are released weekly on the course site with the dataset bundled — most fit in under 50 MB. The pattern is the same every week: read the short theory PDF, implement the algorithm in NumPy or SciPy in 100-200 lines, and answer six to eight short empirical questions.

Project 4 (genomics) gives you a SNP matrix and asks you to recover ancestry via PCA; the trick is to mean-center carefully so the first two components are interpretable. Project 5 (word embeddings) trains a small word2vec on Reuters and evaluates on the analogy task (king minus man plus woman). Project 7 (route optimization) gives you the US national parks dataset and asks for an approximate TSP tour using Christofides. Each project has a public reference solution after the deadline.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS168 Spring 2024', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs168/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs168/handouts.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ml','algorithms','python','numpy','data-science']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs231a-3dvision', 'Stanford CS231A — geometric 3D computer vision', 'Implement classical 3D vision from cameras up — pinhole calibration, the 8-point algorithm for fundamental matrices, dense stereo via window-matching and dynamic programming, structure-from-motion with bundle adjustment, and optical flow (Lucas-Kanade and Horn-Schunck). All in Python with NumPy.', 'Assignments are Jupyter notebooks with a small toolkit (camera projection, image I/O) and synthetic plus real datasets — the Middlebury stereo pairs and a small SfM bundle of Notre-Dame images are pre-included.

Assignment 1 calibrates a camera from a checkerboard, then uses the recovered intrinsics for a single-view metrology problem. Assignment 2 implements the eight-point algorithm with normalization, then triangulates a 3D point cloud from two views. Assignment 3 runs Lucas-Kanade on Sintel sequences and visualizes the resulting flow fields. The final project (groups of three) is open — past teams have done dense SLAM with a phone camera, neural radiance fields on a single object, or human pose tracking from RGB.', 'AI/ML', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS231A Spring 2025', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs231a', '[{"label":"Middlebury Stereo","url":"https://vision.middlebury.edu/stereo/data/","format":"images"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs231a/syllabus.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['computer-vision','3d','python','geometry','slam']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs244b-distsys', 'Stanford CS244B — distributed systems open project', 'Build a substantial distributed systems project in teams over the quarter — past projects include a Raft-replicated key-value store with geo-replication, a Byzantine fault-tolerant log, a chain-replicated object store, and a peer-to-peer file sync over QUIC. Final presentations are six hours of demo day.', 'Unlike the labs-driven 6.5840, CS244B is project-only — you write a proposal in week 2, a milestone report in week 6, and a final paper plus demo. The course gives access to a small Google Cloud allocation for multi-VM experiments.

Week 1-2 is reading mode — pick a paper from the syllabus (Spanner, FaRM, ZAB, EPaxos, Aurora) and decide whether you will reimplement, extend, or build something new. The instructors push hard for measurable results — define a baseline (e.g. single-leader Raft throughput at 5 nodes under 1 percent loss) and a target improvement. Implementation is usually Go, Rust, or C++. The final demo must run live on real network paths, not just on localhost.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS244B Spring 2024', 'https://www.scs.stanford.edu/24sp-cs244b/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"scs.stanford.edu","url":"https://www.scs.stanford.edu/24sp-cs244b/labs/project.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['distributed-systems','consensus','go','rust','research']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs248-graphics', 'Stanford CS248 — interactive computer graphics game project', 'Build an interactive video game that uses geometric modeling, animation curves, particle systems, rigid-body dynamics, and either deformable bodies or a small fluid simulation. Platform is your choice — WebGL, native OpenGL, or a mobile target — but the simulation must run in real time.', 'The early assignments build toolbox pieces — spline editor, mass-spring cloth, particle fountain, broad-phase collision via BVH — that you then compose into the final game. Pick the game concept by week 4 so you can reuse the assignment code rather than rewriting.

For a fluid-based game, implement either Stable Fluids (Stam) on a fixed grid or position-based fluids on particles — both run interactively on a modern GPU. For a destruction-based game, implement Verlet integration with impulse-based collision and use a simple constraint solver for joints. Final demos are graded on technical correctness and visual polish; the staff-favorite past project is a third-person platformer with cloth-driven character clothing.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS248 Winter 2024', 'https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs248/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"web.stanford.edu","url":"https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs248/handouts.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['graphics','simulation','games','physics','interactive']::text[]),
  ('uni-michigan-eecs388-security', 'Michigan EECS 388 — crypto, web, network, appsec, forensics', 'Five offensive-security projects against intentionally vulnerable services. Implement and break AES-CBC padding oracles, exploit XSS and SQL injection on a custom blog, run DNS cache poisoning on a network sandbox, write ROP chains to bypass NX, and recover deleted files from a disk image with Autopsy.', 'Every project ships a VM (or Docker container) with the vulnerable service and a starter notes file. You always work in a sandboxed environment — the course provides a CTF-style scoring server that grades exploits by checking whether you submit the right flag.

The Crypto project hands you a service that decrypts AES-CBC; you write a Vaudenay padding-oracle attack that recovers plaintext byte-by-byte. The Web project is a Flask blog with stored XSS, CSRF, and a SQLi login form — you write JavaScript payloads that exfiltrate session cookies. AppSec gives you a vulnerable C binary with NX but no ASLR — chain gadgets to call system /bin/sh. Forensics gives you a 200 MB disk image; recover the deleted PNG and the chat log inside an alternate data stream.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'University of Michigan', 'OpenSource', 'Michigan EECS 388 Winter 2026', 'https://eecs388.org/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"eecs388.org","url":"https://eecs388.org/schedule.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['security','cryptography','web-security','rop','forensics']::text[]),
  ('uni-brown-cs1380-search', 'Brown CS1380 — distributed search engine in seven milestones', 'Build a distributed web search engine from the ground up — JSON serialization, an actor + RPC layer, gossip-based group membership, a distributed key-value store, a distributed crawler and indexer, and finally deployment on cloud VMs. The final system actually crawls and searches a slice of the live web.', 'The starter is in Node.js — clone the public CS1380 repo and run npm install. Milestone 0 is a centralized version of every component so the API surface is locked in before distribution.

M1 (serialization) handles cyclic objects and function pointers — you write a custom serializer because JSON.stringify cannot round-trip closures. M3 implements gossip-based membership so nodes learn about each other without a central coordinator. M4 builds a consistent-hashed KV store; M5 layers a MapReduce-style executor on top of it; M6 builds the actual search engine — crawler, TF-IDF indexer, and a PageRank job, all expressed as distributed Map+Reduce pipelines. M7 deploys to a cloud provider and benchmarks throughput at 4, 8, 16 nodes.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Brown University', 'OpenSource', 'Brown CS1380 Spring 2024', 'https://cs.brown.edu/courses/csci1380/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"cs.brown.edu","url":"https://cs.brown.edu/courses/csci1380/lectures/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['distributed-systems','javascript','nodejs','search','mapreduce']::text[]),
  ('uni-harvard-cs50ai', 'Harvard CS50 AI — Pac-Man-style classical AI projects in Python', 'Seven Python projects covering classical AI — adversarial search (tictactoe minimax), constraint propagation (minesweeper, crossword), knowledge representation (logic puzzles), uncertainty (PageRank, heredity), optimization, neural networks (traffic-sign classification with TensorFlow), and a Q-learning Nim agent.', 'Each project ships as a small zip with a tester (check50) and a problem spec on the course site. You only edit the labelled TODO functions inside the starter — the harness imports your module and runs hidden tests.

Project 0 (tictactoe) implements minimax with alpha-beta pruning. Project 1 (minesweeper) maintains a set of constraint sets that propagate as cells are revealed. Project 2 (PageRank) implements both the sampling-based and iterative formulations and compares convergence. Project 5 (traffic) trains a small CNN on the German Traffic Sign Recognition Benchmark with Keras — students iterate on architecture and report accuracy in a writeup. Project 6 (Nim) implements tabular Q-learning and plays the agent against itself for 10 000 episodes.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Harvard University', 'OpenSource', 'Harvard CS50 AI 2024', 'https://cs50.harvard.edu/ai/2024/', '[{"label":"GTSRB","url":"https://benchmark.ini.rub.de/gtsrb_news.html","format":"images"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"cs50.harvard.edu","url":"https://cs50.harvard.edu/ai/2024/projects/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ai','python','search','reinforcement-learning','education']::text[]),
  ('uni-harvard-cs50games', 'Harvard CS50 Game Development — Pong to Pokemon in LOVE2D', 'Build eight 2D games in Lua using the LOVE framework — Pong, Flappy Bird, Breakout, Match-3, Super Mario Bros., Legend of Zelda, Angry Birds, and Pokemon. Each week focuses on a specific game-dev concept: collision detection, state machines, tilemaps, physics with Box2D, top-down RPG mechanics, turn-based battles.', 'Install LOVE 11 from love2d.org and clone the CS50G repo — every lecture ships a numbered distro (pong-0 through pong-12) so you can step through the incremental additions. The skeleton uses StateMachine + push (virtual resolution) libraries from the staff.

Week 1 (Pong) introduces the love.draw / love.update game loop. Week 5 (Mario) is the first tilemap-heavy week — you write the level generator and the gravity-based player controller. Week 7 (Angry Birds) is the only one using Box2D physics; you tune restitution and friction until launching a bird feels right. Final project is open-ended — past students have shipped puzzle platformers, roguelikes, and even small networked games via luasocket.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'Harvard University', 'OpenSource', 'Harvard CS50G 2024', 'https://cs50.harvard.edu/games/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"love2d.org","url":"https://love2d.org/wiki/Main_Page"},{"label":"github.com","url":"https://github.com/games50"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['games','lua','love2d','graphics','education']::text[]),
  ('uni-illinois-cs225-mp', 'UIUC CS225 — data structures MPs (mazes, image stitching, graphs)', 'Seven C++ machine problems plus a group final — implement linked lists and binary trees, build a quadtree-based image filterer, write Dijkstra and BFS over real graph datasets (Wikipedia link graph, OSM road network), and culminate in a multi-week algorithmic project on a public dataset.', 'Each MP ships as a Docker-based dev container with starter headers and a Google Test grader. The course Gradescope runs valgrind in addition to correctness, so memory leaks cost points.

MP1 (paint) introduces the PNG class and warms up control flow. MP3 (mosaics) builds a KDTree of average-color tiles, then assembles a photomosaic by nearest-neighbor query. MP_schedule (graph) reads a real bipartite student/course graph and computes a feasible exam schedule by graph coloring. The final project is unique each semester — recent ones include a Wikipedia six-degrees pathfinder using BFS over a 6 GB link graph and a road-network shortest-path service with A* on the OSM California extract.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign', 'OpenSource', 'UIUC CS225 Spring 2024', 'https://courses.grainger.illinois.edu/cs225/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"courses.grainger.illinois.edu","url":"https://courses.grainger.illinois.edu/cs225/sp2024/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['data-structures','cpp','graphs','algorithms','education']::text[]),
  ('uni-nand2tetris', 'Nand2Tetris — build a computer from NAND gates', 'Build a complete computer from first principles — start with NAND gates in an HDL simulator, compose them into ALU and CPU, write a VM and a compiler for the high-level Jack language, then write the Jack OS, and finally ship a Tetris-style game running on your CPU. Twelve projects span hardware to high-level apps.', 'Download the free Nand2Tetris software suite (hardware simulator, CPU emulator, VM emulator, assembler) from nand2tetris.org. Projects 1-5 are in the bundled HDL — you write a few lines of gate composition per chip and the simulator runs functional tests automatically.

Project 6 is your first software piece — write an assembler in any language that translates Hack assembly into 16-bit binary. Project 7-8 implement the VM-to-Hack translator (a stack machine like the JVM). Projects 10-11 build the Jack compiler — a recursive-descent parser plus a code generator targeting the VM. Project 12 is the OS itself — Math, String, Array, Memory, Screen, Keyboard, Sys — written in Jack and self-hosted on your VM. Final demo: load your own game cartridge into your own CPU.', 'Education', 'intermediate', 'Hebrew University of Jerusalem / IDC', 'OpenSource', 'Nand2Tetris 2024', 'https://www.nand2tetris.org/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"nand2tetris.org","url":"https://www.nand2tetris.org/software"},{"label":"nand2tetris.org","url":"https://www.nand2tetris.org/course"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['computer-architecture','compilers','hardware','education','systems']::text[]),
  ('uni-princeton-cos217-shell', 'Princeton COS 217 — Unix shell, BDD package, heap allocator', 'Five C systems projects taught in the Princeton intro-to-systems track — a string library replacement with arena allocation, a binary decision diagram package, a heap memory allocator with first-fit and best-fit policies, a Unix shell with pipes/redirection/globbing, and a small relational database engine.', 'Course materials including assignment specs, starter tarballs, and reference test inputs are published on the course site each semester. You build everything in C on a Linux lab machine — the assignments come with extensive style guides and gradescripts that check both correctness and adherence to the staff coding standard.

Assignment 4 (the shell) is the canonical capstone — you write a Bourne-style shell with lexer, parser, and exec layer that supports pipes between arbitrarily many commands, input and output redirection, and the standard built-ins (cd, setenv, exit). The grader tests against shell session transcripts and fails any output mismatch byte-for-byte. The grading rubric explicitly penalizes memory leaks via Valgrind.', 'OpenSource', 'intermediate', 'Princeton University', 'OpenSource', 'Princeton COS 217 Spring 2022', 'https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spring22/cos217/', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"cs.princeton.edu","url":"https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spring22/cos217/asgts.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['systems','c','shell','memory','education']::text[]),
  ('uni-stanford-cs221-pacman', 'Stanford CS221 — Pac-Man search, MDPs, CSPs, Bayes nets', 'Implement classical AI across six programming assignments — A* search and heuristic design on Pac-Man worlds, value/policy iteration on a Blackjack MDP, CSP solving for course scheduling, particle-filter inference for Ghostbusters, Bayes net inference for medical diagnosis, and a final group project on an open AI problem.', 'Starter code is released as Python zips per assignment — every problem has a submission.py with TODO functions and a grader.py that runs unit tests offline before you upload to Gradescope.

Homework 2 (Blackjack) wants value iteration, then RL with epsilon-greedy Q-learning, then function approximation when the state space gets too large. Homework 4 (CSPs) reuses the AC-3 and backtracking-with-MRV algorithms from Russell and Norvig to schedule courses without conflicts. Homework 6 (Pac-Man ghosts) implements exact inference and then a particle filter that tracks invisible ghosts based on noisy sonar readings — the visualization is the same Pac-Man UI used at Berkeley CS188. Final project (30 percent) is open AI with a 6-page paper deliverable.', 'AI/ML', 'intermediate', 'Stanford University', 'OpenSource', 'Stanford CS221 Summer 2020', 'https://stanford.edu/~cpiech/cs221/index.html', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"stanford-cs221.github.io","url":"https://stanford-cs221.github.io/"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['ai','python','search','mdp','bayes-nets']::text[]),
  ('uni-cmu-15721-oltp', 'CMU 15-721 — advanced in-memory OLTP database project', 'Graduate-level capstone where teams add a substantial feature to an open-source in-memory OLTP database (DuckDB, NoisePage, or Velox). Past projects include vectorized hash joins, learned indexes replacing B-trees, multi-versioned concurrency control, and SIMD-accelerated query execution.', 'Pick a target system in week 1 — DuckDB is the most common because the codebase is small (~200 KLOC) and the build is one CMake away. The course publishes a list of research papers (Hyper, MonetDB/X100, Umbra, Velox) and asks each team to pick a technique to implement and benchmark against the baseline.

Write a one-page proposal in week 2 with a measurable target (e.g. 2x throughput on TPC-H Q1 at scale factor 10 versus the default DuckDB executor). The course requires a midterm demo, a final paper in SIGMOD format, and a public GitHub repo. Many past 15-721 projects have been upstreamed into the host system — your code is expected to be production-quality, with tests and benchmarks.', 'OpenSource', 'advanced', 'Carnegie Mellon University', 'OpenSource', 'CMU 15-721 Fall 2025', 'https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~15721-f25/', '[{"label":"TPC-H","url":"https://www.tpc.org/tpch/","format":"sql"}]'::jsonb, '[{"label":"15721.courses.cs.cmu.edu","url":"https://15721.courses.cs.cmu.edu/spring2024/papers.html"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['databases','research','cpp','performance','oltp']::text[])
